{openings101.org} 1. c4 e5 2. g3 ( {As noted in the introduction, another way people usually get the reversed Dragon variation is via the following move order:} 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. g3 d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bg2 Nb6  ) Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Nb6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. d3 O-O 9. Be3 {This is one of the two most popular and sensible developing schemes for White. We will examine the other one with a3 and b4 in the next Chapter. By developing the bishop to e3, White quickly clears the c1-square as he tries to generate play on the semi-open c-file. Ultimately, it is the c7-pawn that comes under the line of fire, but White also aims at the c5-square, which can serve as a comfortable camp for his pieces; usually with Ne (a) 4-c5 manoeuvre, sometimes with Be3-c5.} ( {Sometimes, White play the flexible} 10. a3 $5 {not showing their cards yet since both plans (with b2-b4 and Be3) are still possible. In that case, I would still recommend that we go for} Re8 {plan} ( {since I am not terribly excited about its main alternative} Be6 11. Be3 Nd5 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Qa4 {etc.}  ) ( {and} a5 {is a slight concession in this move order.}  ) 11. Be3 ( {If White plays} 12. b4 {now, then we transpose into Chapter 2 after} Bf8  ) Bf8 12. Rc1 ( {The main alternative is a hybrid approach} 13. b4 {Black has two good replies:} a5 ( {and} Nd4 $5 14. Ne4 ( 15. Bxd4 $6 exd4 16. Nb5 {runs into a nice tactical refutation:} g5 $1 {We will see a similar motif also in the main line.} 17. h3 Bg7 18. a4 c6 $17 {0-1 (44) Turova,I (2434) -Charochkina,D (2314) Moscow 2011}  ) c6 15. Nxd4 exd4 16. Bg5 {and here, I'd recommend} Qd7 ( {instead of the slightly weakening} f6  ) {In fact, the queen can be put to a good use on the fifth rank:} 17. Qc2 Qf5 $1 18. Bd2 Qh5 $11  ) 14. Bc5 {This is the most principled move.} ( 15. Bxb6 cxb6 16. b5 {seems like an easy solution for White as he compromises Black's pawn structure a bit. However, in turn, Black obtains excellent play on the dark squares after} 