an, at the very least, repeat the position with 12...Bb4, but the fact that we have improved the bishop from e7 to f8 allows us to play} a5 {after all,} ( Bb4 $11  ) {and now if} 15. Rc1 ( 16. Bxb6 cxb6 17. e3 Bf5 $15  ) ( 16. d4 Nc4 17. Nb5 Nxe3 18. fxe3 exd4 19. exd4 Nb4 $17  ) {, then the difference compared to a similar position in 10...a5 line is that now we can prevent the d4-break with the thematic knight jump} Nd4 {(this is not possible with the bishop on e7 since the e5-pawn is hanging)} 16. Bxd4 exd4 {This is one of the most typical structures you will see in the reversed Dragon. As the e-file opens up, Black obtains counterplay against the backward e-pawn.} 17. Nb5 c5 18. Nd2 Bg4 19. Re1 Qd7 $15  ) ( {As usual, White can try} 13. d4 {but Black has no problems whatsoever after} Nc4 $1 14. dxe5 Nxe3 15. fxe3 Bxc3 16. Qxd8 Nxd8 17. bxc3 Rb8 $11 {White cannot keep his extra pawn with such a bad pawn structure. ½-½ (24) Sikorsky,H (2529) -Klimakovs,S (2445) ICCF email 2018}  ) Nd4 13. Ne4 ( 14. Bxd4 $6 {is a slightly premature capture in the view of} exd4 $132 15. Nb5 $6 c5 {and d4-pawn gets the best possible support.} 16. a5 Nd5 17. Nd2 a6 18. Bxd5 axb5 $17 {0-1 (23) Jansen,C (2282) -Bezemer,A (2346) Vlissingen 2003}  ) c6 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Bg5 {As we shall see in some other variations, this attack on the black queen is often a useful provocation in the reversed Dragon. Black has a choice between weakening his structure with ...f7-f6 or} Qd7 {when the queen is slightly misplaced, but the position remains very solid. For example:} 16. Bd2 a5 $11 17. Bxb4 axb4 18. Nc5 Qd6 $132  ) ( 11. Qd2 $5 {is a relatively fresh move from the Armenian kitchen (it was played by Aronian and his second Sargissian) . The main idea is to transfer the other rook to c1.} Bf8 ( {The alternative plan} Bf5 $5 {, employed by MVL also looks very sensible:} 12. Rfc1 Qd7 13. Ne4 Rad8 $11 {Black is well-centralized and has practically equalized. In fact, Sargissian made a slight mistake by