ike there is no difference between the text and} c6 {but after} 15. b4 Be6 16. Nc5 {Black has no choice but to play} Bxc5 17. bxc5 $14 {when the opening of the b-file is clearly in White's favour. The b7- and d4-pawns are rather exposed.}  ) {We've reached a position that was featured in only two classical games so far but is very popular in correspondence chess. While Black is typically very solid, White still has several attempts to grab the initiative on the queenside. If Black weathers the initial storm and centralizes his pieces without major positional concessions, he should be fine or even better in some cases.} 15. b4 {This move was played by Magnus Carlsen, so I promoted it to the main line.} ( {However, probably the most accurate move is} 16. Qc2 $5 {which forces Black to play} c6 {and only then} 17. b4 {After} Bd5 18. Rfe1 {White has overprotected the e2-pawn, so he doesn't need to worry about 17...f5 too much. His plan is to play 18.Nc5 next. Black has several reasonable ways to deal with this and I would recommend} Qe7 $1 {which is more flexible} ( {than} f5 19. Nc5 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 Qd5+ 21. Kg1 Bxc5 22. bxc5 Nd7 23. Bf4 {The arising position can become unpleasant for Black because the isolated d-pawn often becomes an issue in the endgame. Here is an example from a correspondence game:} Re6 24. Qc4 Rae8 25. Qxd5 cxd5 26. Kf1 Kf7 27. a4 h6 28. h4 Ra6 29. a5 $1 Kf6 30. h5 $36 {White was pressing in ½-½ (53) Wunderlich,H (2622) -Haugen,A (2432) ICCF email 2015}  ) 19. a4 ( {If White plays} 20. Nc5 {now, then after} Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Qf7 22. Qb3 Nd5 23. Qc4 Bxc5 24. Qxc5 {we get a position that is similar to 17...f5 but with the key difference that White cannot force a queen trade. Consequently, Black can use his queen to create counterplay, such as} Qh5 $132  ) Rad8 {White has two ways to complete his minority attack. Black is solid enough either way, as can be seen from the correspondence games below.} 20. a5 ( 21. b5 Nd7 22. bxc6 bxc6 23. e3 dxe3 24. Bxe3 c5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (46) Kerr,S (2460) -Green,W (2455) ICCF email 2016}  ) Na8 21. Nc5 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Qf7 23. Kg1 ( 24. Rb1 b6 25. axb6 axb6 26. Nb3 Qd5+ 27. Kg1 Nc7 28. Rbc1 Re6 29. Qc4 Nb5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (30) Jørgensen,B (2313) -Matei,C (2403) ICCF email 2018}  ) Bxc5 24. Qxc5 a6 25. Qa7 Rd7 26. e4 dxe3 27. Rxe3 Red8 28. Rce1 h6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (42) Krakovsky,P (2270) -Kotrc,M (2251) ICCF email 2019}  ) ( 16. Nc5 Bxc5 17. Rxc5 c6 {leads to a typical middlegame in which Black's extra space in the centre and pressure against e2-pawn offset White's long-term positional plusses like the bishop pair and a more compact pawn structure.} 18. Re1 Qd7 19. Qc2 Kh8 20. e4 {This move is a double-edged positional decision since it weakens White's structure significantly.} ( {Going for the minority attack with} 21. b4 a6 22. a4 {is a safer option, although it shouldn't pose Black many problems.} Qf7 23. Ra5 Nd7 24. b5 axb5 25. axb5 Rxa5 26. Bxa5 Bd5 $11  ) dxe3 21. fxe3 Rad8 22. Rc3 Bh3 23. Bf3 Nc8 24. Ra3 Qf5 $132 {0-1 (41) Selen,D (2435) -Johnson,B (2471) ICCF email 2016}  ) ( 16. a4 {is another interesting attempt to create something on the queenside. After} Nd5 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. Rxc5 c6 19. b4 {1-0 (36) Krejci,J (2570) -Nguyen,T (2546) Prague 2019} {we have a clear improvement in} a6 $146 {and if} 20. Qa1 {then Black keeps full control over the position with} Bf7 21. Re1 Nc7 $1 $11 { The knight is placed ideally on c7-square, stopping White from completing the minority attack on the queenside.}  ) Bd5 {This is the point. Now White's 'Dragon' bishop has been neutralized and 16.Nc5 is not nearly as strong as in other lines.} ( {The greedy} Bxa2 $6 {can only lead to problems after} 16. Nc5 $14 Bd5 17. Nxb7 Qd7 18. Nc5 $16  ) 16. a4 ( 17. Nc5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qd5+ $132  ) ( {It is important to point out that White cannot transpose to 15.Qc2 line with} 17. Qc2 $6 {because Black has} f5 { now.}  ) c6 $11 {It is probably fair to say that Black has fully equalized. What follows is a brief analysis of 