{openings101.org}1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Nb6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. a3 O-O 9. b4 {This is generally the most popular system in the reversed Dragon. It is more flexible than the Be3-system as White not only prepares to quickly push b4-b5 but also often develops his bishop to b2 or the rook to b1, which is something that you will not see after 9.Be3. That said, our basic plan does not change a bit - we still plan to put the knight on d4, starting with} Re8 $5 {Just like 9...Be6, this move protects the e5-pawn by tactical means, so there is no need for defensive measures like 9...a6 or 9...f6.} ( Be6 {is considered to be the main line, when White usually continues} 10. d3 ( {or, in the recent times,} 11. b5 $5 Nd4 12. Rb1 ( 13. Nxe5 $4 {loses to} Bb3 14. Qe1 Nc2 $19  ) f6 13. e3 Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 {etc.}  ) a5 11. b5 Nd4 {which leads to a tabiya very similar to the one that we examine in the main line of 9...Re8.}  ) 10. d3 ( {If White plays directly} 11. b5 Nd4 {to win the pawn with} 12. Nxe5 {then we have} Bf6 $1 {x-raying the rook on a1, which makes knight's retreat impossible due to 12...Nxe2+. White's hand is forced to play} 13. f4 Bxe5 14. fxe5 Rxe5 {and, as a result, we get an interesting imbalanced position. White would be in great shape if he had an extra tempo or two to complete his development; however, as it is, the threats of ...Nxb5 and ...Bg4 make it quite difficult for him to keep the material balance. Therefore, people who play this variation with White are usually ready to sacrifice a pawn, hoping to get compensation in the view of the strong bishop pair and pressure on the f-file.} 15. e3 ( 16. Rf4 Nxb5 17. Bb2 {is another decent way to sacrifice the pawn, as in the game 1-0 (25) Minasian, A (2466) -Aronian, L (2551) Yerevan 2000. I would like to recommend a new direction for Black:} Nxc3 $5 $146 18. Bxc3 Rg5 {The rook is going to be useful on the kingside, neutralizing potential attacking threats against g7 and h7 as Black completes his queenside development.} 19. Qc2 c6 20. Be4 Rh5 21. Raf1 Be6 $13 {While White's positional compensation is obvious, Black is in a pretty good shape in absence of concrete threats.}  ) ( 16. a4 $4 Bg4 $19  ) Nxb5 16. Ne4 $5 {This is an attempt to breathe some fresh air into this half-forgotten variation. It was successfully employed by Jeffery Xiong fairly recently, so it should be taken seriously.} ( {Previously, most players have gone for} 17. Nxb5 Rxb5 18. a4 {but Black can neutralize White's threats rather simply with} Rf5 $1 19. a5 ( 20. Rxf5 Bxf5 21. Qf3 Qf6 22. d4 c6 $11  ) Rxf1+ 20. Qxf1 Nd5 21. d4 ( 22. Qd3 Be6 23. Rb1 b6 24. Bb2 Qg5 $15 {0-1 (38) Mesropov, K-Yakovich, Y (2520) Moscow 1990}  ) c6 22. e4 Nc7 23. Be3 Be6 24. Qb1 $44 {0-1 (47) De Lucia,R (2134) -Perina,G (2246) ICCF email 2002}  ) Nd6 {The knight was totally misplaced on b5, so it only makes sense to try to trade it for its strong counterpart on e4.} 17. Qc2 Bf5 18. Rxf5 $1 {A very fine attacking idea, probably prepared by the young American and/or his his team. Otherwise, 16.Qc2 would make little sense.} Nxf5 19. Bb2 {White gets a strong compensation thanks to his well-positioned pieces.} Qe7 $5 {I like Le Quang's pragmatic solution. White has invested quite a bit of material already, so we don't mind giving some of it back to relieve the pressure and complete our development.} ( Rd5 {is engine's main suggestion, but I really dislike defending Black's position after} 20. Rf1 $36 {when White is fully mobilized and has attacking ideas like:} Nd6 21. Bxg7 $1 Nxe4 22. Ba1 $1 $13 {This looks really scary for Black in a practical game, despite the extra rook. I'd prefer Le's simple approach from the game, but if like to gamble you are free to check this position further with the engine.}  ) 20. Rf1 c6 21. Bxe5 Qxe5 $11 {1-0 (40) Xiong, J (2709) -Le, Q (2709) chess24.com INT 2020}  ) Bf8 {We have reached the tabiya of this variation. White has a number of critical options at this point, so 