{openings101.org} 1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Nb6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 {In this chapter, we will examine less popular alternatives for White in this position. Among them,} 8. Rb1 {is the most notable one. The point behind it is to provoke ...a5, when White is hoping to take advantage of a slightly weakened position of the b6-knight. We have seen a similar idea with a2-a4 in the first chapter, but the difference is that Rb1 is a much less committal move for White.} ( {The double fianchetto approach with} 9. b3 {leads to a relatively quiet manoeuvring battle, especially compared to positions from Chapter 2 which have a lot of tactical tension on the queenside.} O-O 10. Bb2 {Just like in most of the similar positions from the first two chapters, I prefer} Re8 {over 9...Be6, 10...f6 for the reasons already explained in the Introduction (e-file, safer king) .} ( {It is very easy for Black to think that it is the right time to play the aggressive} f5 {since there is no pressure on his centre, but this is not such a good approach because of} 11. d3 Be6 12. Rc1 Bf6 13. e4 $1 {Here, White's extra tempo does play a role as Black is not in time to organize counterplay against the d3-pawn. So, White blocks the e5-pawn and gets the upper hand in the centre, one way or another.} f4 ( Nb4 14. Ne1 $14  ) 14. Ne2 $14  ) 11. Rc1 Bf8 ( {Besides the semi-automatic bishop retreat, there is also} Bf5 $5 {played by Hikaru Nakamura. We have seen this plan before in the games of MVL and Carlsen. Black simply completes his queenside development and prepares to exchange the light-squared bishops after ...Qd7, .. .Bh3, etc.} 12. d3 Qd7 13. Ne4 f6 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 Bh3 {(eliminating White's bishop pair advantage and weakening his king)} 16. Bxh3 Qxh3 17. b4 a6 18. a3 Qe6 19. Nd2 Rad8 $11 { With such strong centralization, Black should be fine. He just needs to resolve the issue of the backward c-pawn. 0-1 (68) Dubov,D (2699) -Nakamura,H (2736) chess24.com INT 2020}  ) 12. d3 ( {Fabiano Caruana recently tried to save a tempo on a d2-d3, by playing} 13. Ne4 $5 {immediately. While this seems a bit risky considering that Black can play} f5 {, things actually become very complicated after this principled move. The surprising} 14. Nc3 $1 {is more critical} ( {than} 15. Nc5 e4 16. Ne1 Bd6 $5 $146 17. d3 Qe7 $13 {because the knight is quite shaky on c5 in this position.}  ) e4 15. Ne1 {This is a typical hypermodernist provocation. White has invited Black to push his central pawn, but now he is ready to attack it with d2-d3. Among several alternatives, Black's best reply might just be the equally provocative} Nb4 $1 {which is something no one would find without the help of an engine, so please take notes here.} {The point is that after} 16. a3 {we go back to} ( {In the case of the immediate} 17. d3 {we play} c6 $1 {(a strong quiet move, supporting ...Nb4-d5)} 18. dxe4 ( 19. a3 N4d5  ) Qxd1 19. Rxd1 fxe4 20. a3 N4d5 21. Nxe4 Bf5 22. Nd2 Rxe2 $11  ) ( 17. f3 {is the other way to undermine black centre, but it is less critical.} e3 18. dxe3 Bc5 $11  ) Nc6 $1 {, much in the same way as White played Nc3-e4-c3. The point is that we have provoked a serious weakening in White's queenside structure, so after} 17. d3 {we can attack the b3-pawn with} Be6 {and if} 18. b4 a5 19. b5 Nd4 $132 {weakness of the b3-square is still an issue for White.}  ) {Black has several good options at this junction. Perhaps the most interesting one is} a5 $5 {This is just a generally useful move in this structure, but it also keeps White busy worrying about ...a5-a4 in some variations.} ( Nd4 {is the most natural continuation of our previous play. After} 13. Nd2 c6 14. e3 Ne6 {we get something very similar to what we have seen in Chapter 2, only with white pawns on a2 and b3, instead of a3 and b4. It is exactly this slight difference that gives White a new option:} 15. Nc4 $5 ( 16. Nf3 Ng5 17. Nxg5 Qxg5 $11 {0-1 (35) Mareco,S (2664) -Hansen,E (2616) Chess. com INT 2017}  ) Nxc4 16. bxc4 { 1-0 (54) Salceanu,V (2528) -Hugentobler,P (2483) ICCF email 2002. This recapture is possible thanks to the pawn standing on b3. Now, while this position still seems kind of okay for Black, it might be a little worse in reality because the knight on e6 is in the way of several other black pieces and could be particularly awkwardly placed if White manages to push his d-pawn forward.}  ) 13. Nd2 {The most flexible move.} ( 14. a3 {weakens the b3-pawn and we can take advantage of it with} Bg4 15. h3 ( 16. Ne4 Nd4 {is a dream position for Black in the reversed Dragon.}  ) Be6 $1 { The best square for the bishop, keeping an eye on both flanks.} ( {The bishop is somewhat out of play on} Bh5  ) 16. Ne4 Nd4 $11 {The final part of Black's opening strategy is executed with a tempo, which means that we are doing great. In fact, White quickly handed over the initiative in the following game:} 17. Ned2 $6 Nxf3+ 18. Nxf3 f6 19. Qc2 c5 $15 {Black got a sort of a Maroczy bind with colours reversed going in ½-½ (69) Murshed, N (2449) -Rahman, S (2252) Dhaka 2016}  ) ( 14. Ne4 {is a sharp move as it allows} a4 $146 ( Nd4 $6 {however, runs into} 15. Nxe5 $1 Rxe5 16. e3 $14  ) {and now White's best bet is the classical exchange sacrifice} 15. Rxc6 $5 bxc6 16. Nxe5 axb3 17. axb3 {which leads to a double edged-game. Black can keep the extra pawn with} c5 $13 ( {or give it up with} Nd5 $5 18. Nxc6 Qd7 19. Ne5 Qb5 $13 { to activate his pieces.}  )  ) Bg4 $5 $146 { This new and logical move should give Black a good game.} ( f6 {is a solid and sound alternative.} 14. Nc4 Be6 15. Nxb6 cxb6 16. e3 Qd7 17. Na4 Rad8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (18) Vaillant,F (2168) -Pedersen,S (2132) ICCF email 2015}  ) 14. Re1 ( 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Re1 Bh3 $13  ) ( 15. Nb5 $5 a4 16. Rxc6 bxc6 17. Bxc6 Bh3 18. Re1 $13  ) ( 15. h3 Be6 $11 {allows us to win an important tempo with ...Qd7 next.}  ) Qd7 15. Na4 Nxa4 16. bxa4 Ra6 $5 $11  ) ( 9. a4 {is hardly critical since Black can play} a5 {with a clear conscie