ore careful here because his dark squares are quite vulnerable.} 16. f4 ( 17. fxe3 {is a bit suspect since after} Bg5 $1 {there may not be anything better for White than to sacrifice an exchange with} 18. Rf4 Bxf4 19. gxf4 Bxa2 20. Nc3 Qe7 21. Nc2 Bb3 $15 {0-1 (53) Atakhan,A (2298) -Darini,P (2424) Teheran 2020}  ) b5 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. Rxc5 Qb6 19. Rc1 Bxa2 20. Bxc6 bxc6 21. Qc2 Bd5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (30) Stephens,M (2295) -Carapinha,F (2319) ICCF email 2017}  ) ( 12. a3 {is also decent when we can play for the kingside initiative with} f5 ( a4 {is not that effective as after 11.Rc1 because of} 13. Bxb6 cxb6 14. Nd2  ) 13. b4 $5 {This is the critical reply, hinting at the weakness of the e5-pawn.} ( 14. Rc1 {Just as in 11.Rc1 line, the position of white rook on c1 is a signal for} a4 $5 ( Kh8 {is a quiet alternative.} 15. Na4 Nd5 16. Bc5 Bd6 $1 {This is a fairly standard way to ensure that white knight doesn't get to c5.} 17. Nd2 ( 18. e4 fxe4 19. dxe4 Nf6 20. Re1 Bg4 $11  ) Rb8 18. Bxd6 cxd6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (22) Zvjaginsev,V (2656) -Timofeev,A (2320) Moscow 2002}  ) ( {We should not rush with} f4 $2 {because of} 15. gxf4 $1 exf4 16. Bxb6 cxb6 17. d4 $16 {and White will dominate in the center after the inevitable d4-d5 push.}  ) 15. Bxb6 ( 16. Nd2 Nd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (38) Kharlamov,V (2495) -Krivic,D (2525) ICCF email 2008}  ) cxb6 16. Nxa4 e4 17. Ne1 Bg5 $1 {This is an important difference compared to a similar position after 11.Rc1.} ( {There, we play} e3 {but in this particular position this move is an inferior choice because of} 18. fxe3 Bg5 19. Rf4 Bxf4 20. gxf4 $14 {when inclusion of moves a3 and ...f5 is in White's favor.}  ) 18. e3 ( 19. Ra1 Nd4 20. Nc3 Bb3 21. Qb1 e3 22. f4 Bf6 23. Bxb7 Ra5 $36 {1/2-1/2 (31) Zhak,B (2556) -Goncharenko,G (2491) ICCF email 2009}  ) exd3 19. Nxd3 Rxa4 20. Qxa4 Qxd3 $13 {1/2-1/2 (31) Bergmann,M (2308) -Kruse,H (2650) FICGS email 2018}  ) ( 14. Na4 f4 {is not a problem now that white knight is on the rim.} 15. Bc5 Nxa4 16. Bxe