7}  ) Rc8 $1 {This precise move should be remembered.} ( {The immediate} f5 {is not so strong because of} 13. Rfd1 Bf6 14. e3 {and White will carry out d4 in favorable circumstances.} Bf7 ( Nb4 $2 {is the antidote in the main line, but it simply doesn't work here:} 15. a3 Nxd3 16. Ne1 e4 17. Nxd3 exd3 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. Rxd3 $18  ) 15. d4 e4 16. Nd2 Bh5 17. Rdc1 $14 {We did not manage to set up a blockade on d5, so White's positional advantage is indisputable.}  ) 13. Rbc1 ( {If White plays} 14. Rfd1 {, preparing 14.e3 and 15.d4, as in the game 0-1 (65) Jones,G (2615) -Howell,D (2693) London 2015, then we play} Nd4 $1 $146 15. Nxd4 ( 16. Nxe5 {runs into} Rxc3 $1 17. bxc3 Nxe2+ $19 {This is why we had to play 12...Rc8!}  ) exd4 16. Ne4 Bd5 $1 { Black takes the initiative with this move. White can pick between a passive middlegame:} 17. Rdc1 ( {or a slightly worse endgame:} 18. Qxd4 Bxa2 19. Qxd8 Rfxd8 $15 {The bishop pair and queenside majority are strong assets for Black.}  ) Bc6 18. Qd1 h5 $1 {(provoking/creating some kingside weaknesses)} 19. h4 f5 20. Nd2 Bb4 21. Nf3 f4 $36  ) f5 14. Rfd1 Bf6 15. a3 ( 16. e3 {is now strongly met by} Nb4 $1 17. d4 ( 18. a3 {is wrong because of an important tactical detail} Nxd3 19. Ne1 Nxb2 20. Rxd8 Nxa4 21. Rxf8+ Kxf8 $1 $19  ) e4 18. Ne1 Qd6 19. a3 Nd5 $11 { and we have managed to block the d-pawn. If White is not careful, he could fall under a kingside attack after ...g5, ... f4 / ...h5, etc.}  ) Kh8 ( {Another sensible plan that Black has at his disposal is} Rc7 $5 16. e3 Rd7 {not only preventing the central break, but also creating pressure against the d-pawn.} 17. Nd2 $5 f4 $1 $132 {1/2-1/2 (43) Privara,I (2520) -Stephan,J (2561) ICCF email 2012} ( Rxd3 18. Nc4 $36  )  ) 16. e3 Bf7 $1 {A strong maneuver that discourages White from pushing the central pawn.} 17. Nd2 ( 18. d4 exd4 19. exd4 Bh5 20. Nb5 f4 $1 $132  ) Bh5 18. Bf3 Be8 $1 19. Qb3 {All of this was seen in the game between two very strong players 1-0 (37) Gashimov,V (2