{openings101.org} 1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Nb6 {In this chapter, we examine alternatives to 6.Nf3. White has two very interesting moves to get independent positions here. The sharper one is} 6. e3 {intending to complete development with Nge2 and then attack the centre with f2-f4.} ( 7. d3 {is a more positional alternative. White postpones his kingside development in order to slow down Black's queenside development.} Be7 ( {The point is that} Nc6 {might be premature because White always has an option to capture on c6 and damage our pawn structure. The following game is a good example of White's strategy:} 8. Be3 Be7 9. Bxc6+ $5 bxc6 10. Rc1 O-O 11. Nf3 Bd6 12. Ne4 {The c5-square will be a very comfortable outpost for white pieces.} Nd5 13. Qc2 Bd7 14. O-O Qe7 15. Bc5 f5 16. Ned2 {Black has some compensation for his poor pawn structure in theory, but his bishops are inactive so white position is just easier to play.} Rae8 ( f4 17. Ne4 $14  ) 17. e4 $1 Nf6 18. d4 Nxe4 19. Nxe4 fxe4 20. Nxe5 $14 {1-0 (48) Esipenko,A (2682) -Gadimbayli,A (2470) Tornelo INT 2020}  ) 8. Be3 O-O 9. Rc1 {This becomes a ''wait-and-see game", as super-GM Ding put it. Both sides are trying to make useful moves before the other side commits with Nf3 or ...Nc6, respectively. Fortunately, Black has enough such moves. Considering our discussions from the first three chapters, it should already be clear by now that} Re8 10. a3 Bf8 {is going to be a useful regrouping.} 11. Qc2 {However, now we have to think of something else. There are two options:} h6 {This move is the most consistent with our plan to develop the knight to c6 and it is useful as it covers the vulnerable g5-square.} ( {or 'admit a defeat' with} c6 $5 12. Nf3 {This means that our knight will not go to the most natural c6-square, after all, but this is actually not a big deal since we have another reasonable developing scheme:} Bf5 13. O-O N8d7 {and, on top of that, we have solved the issue of the backward c7-pawn.} 14. b4 ( 15. Bg5 f6 16. e4 $5 Be6 17. Be3 c5 ( a5 $5  ) 18. Nd2 Nb8 $1 19. Nb3 N6d7 20. Nd5 Na6 21. f4 Rc8 $13 {0-1 (74) Ohtake,S (2382) -Casabona,C (2586) ICCF email 2016}  ) a5 15. Rb1 axb4 16. axb4 Nd5 $11 {1-0 (61) Bachmann,A (2653) -Brodsky,D (2379) New York 2017}  ) {At this point, White has kind of ran out of useful moves, so it is probably the most prudent to play} 12. Nf3 ( {GM Pantsulaia tried an interesting plan} 13. h3 a6 ( c6 $5  ) 14. g4 $5 {This gives White some space on the kingside but weakens f4- and h4-squares. His opponent found a good way to exploit it:} N8d7 15. Nf3 Nf6 $1 16. Nd2 c6 17. Nce4 Nfd5 18. Bc5 Nf4 $132 {1-0 (55) Pantsulaia,L (2593) -Sargsyan,S (2481) Batumi 2018}  ) ( 13. b4 {is a premature action with such a poor development and it was duly punished in the following game:} a5 14. Bc5 axb4 15. axb4 Bxc5 16. bxc5 N6d7 17. c6 Nxc6 18. Bxc6 bxc6 $15 {1/2-1/2 (53) Pridorozhni,A (2568) -Makhmutov,R (2437) Moscow 2017}  ) {Now, we can safely complete our queenside development.} Nc6 13. Ne4 Be6 14. O-O {Compared to other similar positions in the reversed Dragon, here Black cannot play ...Nd4 because of the pressure against the c7-pawn. Therefore, we need another plan. Considering White's queenside situation, the most logical one is} a5 $1 {preparing to fix the queenside with ...a4 next.} 15. Rfe1 ( 16. Nc5 Bxc5 17. Bxc5 a4 $11 {This is an improved version of similar positions because White cannot push his b-pawn forward.} 18. Bxb6 ( 19. Nd2 Nd5 { White bishop is actually quite misplaced on c5 since it blocks the file for his heavy pieces. Meanwhile, Black will prepare an exchange of light-squared bishops.} 20. Ne4 Qc8 21. Rfe1 Bh3 22. Bh1 Be6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (36) Mercadal Benejam,J (2409) -De la Rosa Solorzano,J (2344) ICCF email 2018}  ) cxb6 19. Nd2 Nd4 20. Qd1 {1-0 (51) Ivanchuk,V (2766) -Fressinet, L (2700) Beijing 2012} Bg4 21. Re1 Qd7 $132  ) a4 $13 {Black should be quite comfortable now.} 16. Nfd2 $5 {Interesting manoeuvring by GM Ivanchuk. White is keeping the tension in the position.} ( {Alternatively,} 17. Bc5 f5 18. Ned2 Bxc5 19. Qxc5 Bf7 $132 { already seems more pleasant for Black.}  ) Bd5 17. Bh3 $1 {An original way to stop ...f7-f5.} Be6 18. Bg2 ( {Perhaps it was better for White to simplify with} 19. Bxe6 $5 Rxe6 20. Bc5 Nd4 21. Qd1 Bxc5 22. Nxc5 Rc6 23. e3 Ne6 24. Nde4 Nxc5 25. Rxc5 Rxc5 26. Nxc5 Qd5 $11  ) Bd5 19. Nc4 {Now Black finally got to play} Nd4 {and after the mass-exchanges:} 20. Bxd4 exd4 21. Nxb6 cxb6 22. Nd2 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Qd5+ 24. Nf3 b5 $15 {his position was for preference because of the extra space and the queenside potential. We should not automatically discount doubled b-pawns as bad in such positions - they can often be undoubled and they cover some important squares, like c4 and c6 in this case. ½-½ (28) Ivanchuk,V (2766) -Khairullin,I (2638) Jurmala 2012}  ) Nc6 7. Nge2 {Black have tried many moves here and it wouldn't be a mistake to play 7...Be7 or 7... Qd3, for example. However, my view on this whole repertoire is that when we have an opportunity to make an ambitious opening choice with Black, we should seriously consider it because we typically control more space and White's extra tempo may not always be so important. With this big-picture considerations, let me recommend} h5 $1 {here. This move is fairly typical, principled even, for fianchetto setups in which white knight is not on f3. Needless to say, it leads to sharp positions and we should be very well prepared to play like this. The reward is that we practically eliminate White's main idea in this position, f2-f4, and can sometimes even take the initiative in the opening (if White makes even one inaccuracy) .} 8. d4 {As they say, the best way to deal with the flank attack is to counter-attack in the centre.} ( 9. h3 {allows Black to execute a typical double pawn-break combo:} h4 10. g4 f5 $1 11. gxf5 Bxf5 {As a result of it, Black has shattered White's kingside structure developed an important piece with a tempo. White needs to react in the centre} 12. d4 exd4 {This is the most natural reply,} ( {but there is also something to be said for the more ambitious} Qd6 $5 $146 { which leads into interesting tactical complications:} 13. d5 ( {or} 14. e4 exd4 15. exf5 dxc3 16. bxc3 Qxd1+ 17. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 18. Kc2 Bc5 $132  ) Qg6 14. Rg1 Bc2 $1 {(preparing an original queen entrapment)} 15. Be4 $1 Qxe4 16. Nxe4 Bxd1 17. Kxd1 ( {White can also keep the material balance with} 18. dxc6 O-O-O 19. cxb7+ Kxb7 20. Bd2 Bc2 $13 {but then his light squares are more vulnerable. 1/2-1/2 (36) Johansen, J (2339) -Sjøl, H (2301) ICCF email 2021}  ) Nxd5 18. N2c3 Nxc3+ 19. Nxc3 Nd8 $1 {(improving the knight)} 20. Ne4 Ne6 21. Ke2 $11 {White has full positional compensation for the pawn, but not more.}  ) 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. exd4 Be7 $1 $146 {I believe that Black's previous play can be improved considerably with} 15. O-O ( 16. Bxb7 {I think that any educated chess player should routinely give away such pawns for the lead in development.} O-O 17. Bg2 Rb8 18. O-O Qd7 $132 {Black's position is clearly easier to play.}  ) O-O 16. Re1 Qd7 $11  ) ( 9. h4 {is overly cautious since it gives away a very important outpost on g4. Black gets a comfortable game with} Bg4 10. d4 exd4 11. exd4 Bd6 12. O-O Qd7 $132  ) h4 9. O-O {This is the critical move despite being much less popular than 9.d5 for some reason. White should keep central tension to have an option of opening it at the right moment. Otherwise, Black can develop his kingside initiative without any major distractions.} ( 10. d5 {closes the centre, which typically works in the favour of Black who has already made strides with his h-pawn.} Nb8 11. O-O ( {White can also postpone castling. Several attempts that were met in practice didn't change the initial impression that Black has an upper hand in this type of position.} 12. b3 Na6 { The knight gets naturally redeployed via this square.} 13. Bb2 h3 ( Bd7 $5 $15  ) 14. Be4 $6 ( 15. Bf3 Qf6 16. Nc1 N