{openings101.org}1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. O-O {This move order is designed to prepare a quick d2-d4, for which White does not need to play Nc3.} ( 7. d4 $2 {is premature, though, in the view of} exd4 8. O-O ( {I once won a funny miniature in a blitz game when my opponent completely misplayed the opening with:} 9. Nxd4 $2 Bb4+ 10. Kf1 Nde7 $17 11. Be3 $2 ( 12. e3 $8  ) Bc5 {0-1 (9) Fonsofan (2373) -crotexan2210 (2484) Internet Chess Club 2018}  ) Bc5 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. Nbxd4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 c6 $15  ) {Black has two basic replies and in this database, I will suggest a more flexible one} Nb6 {This way we stop 7.d4 and try to steer the game toward the well-known positions that we have studied in the first three chapters.} ( Be7 {is also a decent option, although in this case White can play} 7. d4 e4 8. Ne5 {and after the best} f5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 { we get an interesting pawn structure. While Black is super-solid in the centre, his queenside structure could become a problem in the long term. It shouldn't be anything special for White, but it is a slight positional concession that we can avoid by playing simply 6...Nb6. If you are interested in this variation, nevertheless, I provide some important variations below:} 10. Qc2 ( 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Nb3 {is a slow positional approach that can easily backfire for White.} Qe8 13. Bd2 {1-0 (41) Milos,G (2598) -Santos,M (2353) Sao Paulo 2005} h5 $1 14. Na5 h4 15. Rc1 Bd7 $36  ) Bd7 $5 ( Qd7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Bf4 Ba6 14. Rfc1 Rac8 {1-0 (44) Wang Hao (2718) -Karjakin,S (2788) Ningbo 2011 CBM 144 [Marin,M]} 15. Qd2 $14  ) 11. f3 $1 ( 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Nc4 Nb4 $1 14. Qd2 Be6 15. Ne5 Qd5 16. a3 Na6 17. b4 c5 $1 $132  ) exf3 12. Rxf3 O-O 13. Nc3 $13  ) {At this point, White can transpose directly into the main line with 7.Nc3, but in this chapter we will examine an alternative way of development -} 7. b3 {By playing this way, White takes advantage of the fact that his knight is still on b1 in three ways. Firstly, it allows him to win a tempo while developing the bishop to b2 since e5-pawn needs to be protected. Secondly, the open diagonal facilitates d4-break in some cases. And finally, the knight can be developed to d2, which is a more flexible square for it in some cases because it can go to both c4 and e4.} ( 8. d3 {is an alternative move order to get the double-fianchetto type of position.} Be7 9. Nbd2 {This is required before pushing the b-pawn} ( {since} 10. b3 $6 {runs into} Bf6 $1 11. e4 ( 12. Bb2 $4 e4 $19  ) Bg4 $15  ) O-O 10. a3 a5 11. b3 Be6 12. Bb2 f6 13. Qc2 ( {The following game is very instructive for this type of position, so I would like to provide a large part of it here even if it is not particularly relevant from a theoretical point of view. On that note, let me make a general remark that goes for the whole reversed Dragon repertoire: it is just as important to understand how to play typical middlegames and even endgames properly as it is to know the opening theory laid out in this database.} 14. Rc1 Qd7 15. Ne4 Bh3 16. Nc5 Bxc5 17. Rxc5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Nd8 $1 { } 19. Qd2 a4 20. b4 Ne6 21. Rcc1 Nc8 $1 { Impressive manoeuvring by Fedoseev.} 22. Qc2 Nd6 23. Rfd1 Nb5 24. Qc4 c6 25. e4 Kh8 26. h3 Rfd8 27. Qc2 Qe7 28. Rd2 Rd6 29. Rcd1 Qd8 30. h4 Nbd4 31. Bxd4 Nxd4 32. Nxd4 Rxd4 33. Rc1 Qd7 $15 { 0-1 (61) Wang,H (2729) -Fedoseev,V (2662) Dubai 2014}  ) Qd7 14. Rfd1 ( {White's main plan is to eventually open the centre with the help of d3-d4 break. For this purpose,} 15. e3 { is the quickest possibility. However, we can interfere with White's plans with} Bf5 $5 16. Ne4 Qe6 17. Nfd2 ( 18. Nh4 {is objectively better, although Black is typically doing well after the following exchange} Bh3 $11  ) Rfd8 18. Nc4 {1-0 (30) Lie,K (2421) -Bischoff,K (2554) Bled 2002} Rd7 $15  ) Rfd8 $13 {Now d4-break has been slowed down. This position offers rich possibilities for both sides. Let us examine the most relevant practical material.} 15. Nc4 ( 16. Rac1 Bf8 ( Qe8 $5 { is a cool move. The queen can be moved to several squares, depending on what White does.} 17. Qb1 ( 18. e3 Qg6  ) Qf8 18. Qa1 Qf7 19. d4 e4 20. Nxe4 Bxb3 $13 {Black seems to have an easier play in this imbalanced position.} 21. Re1 Na4 22. Ned2 Nxb2 23. Qxb2 a4 $1 24. e4 Na5 25. d5 Qf8 $1 $132 { 0-1 Milos,G (2586) -Cubas,J (2528) /Santos 2012/CBM 152 Extra (52)}  ) 17. Nc4 ( 18. d4 $2 {was a premature break that was swiftly punished.} exd4 19. Ne4 Qf7 20. Nxd4 Nxd4 21. Rxd4 Rxd4 22. Bxd4 Bxa3 $17 {0-1 (30) Giddins,S (2315) -Gurevich,M (2667) Amsterdam 2000}  ) Qf7 18. Qb1 Bd5 ( Nxc4 19. bxc4 a4 $132 { is an interesting stuctural transformation, although there may be no need to unite white pawns.}  ) 19. e3 Nd7 20. e4 ( 21. Qc2 Nc5 $132  ) Be6 21. d4 {White finally carries out his central break, but his queenside remains tender even so.} exd4 22. Nxd4 Nxd4 23. Rxd4 {1/2 (43) Malakhov,V (2714) -Lastin,A (2617) Olginka 2011} b5 $1 24. Ne3 c5 25. Rd3 c4 26. bxc4 bxc4 $15  ) Qe8 { This queen manoeuvre is quite thematic. Her majesty was becoming vulnerable on the d-file and it is quietly moving toward the kingside.} 16. Nfd2 ( 17. Nxb6 cxb6 18. d4 $2 {is the most straightforward continuation. ½-½ (22) Galyas,M-Anka,E/Budapest 2004/ (35) , but it runs into} Qf7 $1 19. dxe5 Bxb3 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Qc3 fxe5 $17  ) ( 17. d4 $6 {has a tactical drawback related to b3-pawn, as well, though a sneakier one this time:} a4 $1 $15 { 0-1 (90) Ponomariov,R (2723) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2710) Beijing 2011}  ) Bf8 17. Rac1 Qf7 $13 { The maneuvering continues. Black's chances are not worse since White always needs to attend to his vulnerable queenside pawns.}  ) {At this point, Black can keep developing his kingside as if nothing had happened, but I would like to recommend a more ambitious approach} Be6 $5 { which has been endorsed by top players Nepomniachtchi and Nakamura. Black's plan to castle queenside may seem risky at first, but it makes perfect sense for a couple of reasons. On the one hand, White's relatively modest opening scheme allows for this kind of development since there is no pressure on black pieces (like a3-b4-b5 that we saw in Chapter 2) . On the other, by putting two heavy pieces on the d-file, Black hinders White's main plan, the execution of d4-break.} ( {Black have also been doing fine with a more classical approach:} Be7 8. Bb2 f6 {The main difference compared to most other reversed Dragon lines is that White can push} 9. d4 {very early here. On the bright side for Black, after} e4 { there is no 10.Ne5 as in 6...Be7 7.d4 e4 line, so we get to keep our queenside pawn structure intact. I will not go much into this variation and will limit myself to providing two interesting examples:} 10. Ne1 ( 11. Nfd2 f5 12. e3 O-O 13. f3 exf3 14. Nxf3 Be6 15. Nc3 Nd5 16. Na4 b6 17. Qc2 Qe8 18. Rae1 Rd8 $13 {1/2-1/2 (49) Fernandez Vicente,C (2492) -Dutra Neto,A (2459) ICCF email 2013}  ) f5 11. f3 {White should carry out this freeing break sooner or later.} exf3 12. Nxf3 Nd5 13. Qd3 O-O 14. e3 Be6 15. a3 Qd7 16. Nbd2 Rad8 { The position is roughly balanced. Black is well-centralized, while White is hoping to make something out of his pawn centre and fianchettoed bishops in the long run.} 17. Rac1 Nb6 18. b4 a6 $13 {1-0 (53) Nakamura,H (2802) -Hammer,J (2677) Stavanger NOR 2015}  ) ( Bd6 $5 {is an attempt to improve on the previous line since the bishop defends the e5-pawn, so there is no need to play ...f6 any more. After} 8. Bb2 O-O 9. d3 ( 10. d4 exd4 11. Nxd4 Be5 $1 $11  ) {it is probably best to play} Re8 $5 {intending to retreat the bishop to f8.} 10. Nc3 Bf8 11. Rc1 f6 12. Ne4 a5 $1 13. a3 Be6 { This position shares a lot of similarities to those that we have studied in 7. d3 line in this chapter, so I suggest that you compare it to that analysis.} 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 Qd7 16. Qc2 Bd5 17. Rc1 Rad8 $13 {1/2-1/2 (45) Mackintosh,I (2386) -Blake,M (2315) ICCF email 2018}  ) 8. Bb2 f6 9. Nc3 {Most white players prefer patient development,} ( {even though it is also possible to immediately push} 10. d4 {After} e4 11. Ne1 f5 12. f3 exf3 13. Nxf3 ( 14. Bxf3 {is a clearly inferior choice because the knight is misplaced on e1. Black got the initiative in a straightforward way in the following game:} Qd7 15. e3 O-O-O 16. Nc3 h5 $1 17. Bxh5 $6 {This is very risky.} ( 18. Ng2 {is a bit better, although Black still keeps the edge with} Bb4 $1 19. Qc2 Bxc3 20. Bxc3 Bd5 $15  ) g5 $40 { 0-1 (72) Gorodetzky,D (2489) -Le,Q (2709) Chess.com INT 2020}  ) Be7 14. Nc3 Nd5 {we have a type of position that was already discussed in 7...Be7 line. Nakamura played a slower plan with Qd3 and Nbd2 against Hammer, but here White has some additional, more direct, options:} 15. e4 $5 $146 {This new idea puts the most pressure on Black.} ( 16. Ne5 {is a classical plan, although hardly problematic for Black in this version.} O-O 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Qd3 Nb4 19. Qd2 Bg5 20. e3 Qd6 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (32) Ludgate,A (2442) -Bleker,F (2382) FICGS email 2015}  ) Nxc3 16. Bxc3 fxe4 17. Nd2 {White's idea was to open the f-file, so that Black cannot castle kingside. Fortunately, we are well-prepared for this scenario as} Qd7 { prepares to evacuate the king to the other flank.} ( Nxd4 $4 {is suicidal in the view of} 18. Qh5+ g6 19. Qe5 $18  ) {White can now open the centre for his bishops in one of two ways, although none of them should pose serious problems to Black:} 18. d5 $5 ( {and} 19. Nxe4 O-O-O 20. Nc5 Bxc5 21. dxc5 Qe7 $1 22. Qh5 g6 23. Bf6 gxh5 24. Bxe7 Nxe7 25. Rfe1 Bd5 26. Rxe7 h4 $11  ) Qxd5 19. Nxe4 O-O-O 20. Bxg7 Rhe8 $11  ) ( 10. Qc1 $5 {is an interesting move, preparing Rd1 and d4.} Qd7 11. Rd1 ( 12. Nc3 {is a tricky alternative. This position can also arise from 9.Nc3 Qd7 10.Qc1 move order.} Bb4 $5 {I like this move, played by Hikaru Nakamura, even though it may not seem like Black's most straightforward choice in this position. The idea is to prepare ...Bxc3 as a response to White's d2-d4. This exchange allows Black to take full control over the light squares in the centre.} ( {Black needs to be aware of the following trick:} O-O-O $6 13. d4 $1 exd4 14. Rd1 $36 {Nc3-b5 is in the air and White obtains a serious initiative.}  ) ( Nd5 {is the simplest way to fight against White's central break (with a similar idea as 10...Bb4) , although there is something odd about playing twice with the same piece in the opening. However, White cannot really take advantage of that even if he plays the thematic} 13. d4 ( 14. Ne4 {is met by} Bh3 15. Bxh3 Qxh3 16. d4 Qg4 17. Nc3 Nxc3 18. Qxc3 exd4 19. Qc4 O-O-O $11 {1/2-1/2 (19) Hallqvist,N (2109) -Wilson,N (2120) FICGS email 2020}  ) Nxc3 14. Qxc3 e4 15. Nh4 Bd5 {Now, White needs to push} 16. f3 {one way or the other.} ( {The alternative is to go for an endgame with} 17. Qe3 Qe6 18. f3 exf3 19. Qxe6+ Bxe6 20. Bxf3 O-O-O 21. Rfd1 Nb4 22. e4 Bd6 $11 { The first step toward containing the hanging pawns in the centre has been accomplished. White cannot push them forward without creating some weaknesses. In the long run, Black will coordinate his forces to try to attack and destroy them.}  ) exf3 17. Bxf3 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 O-O-O 19. Rad1 {Here, I like the following bishop maneuver:} Bb4 $1 20. e4 Rhe8 21. Nf5 Ba5 $132  ) 13. Rd1 ( 14. d4 {is even less attractive here than in 10...Nd5 line because after} Bxc3 15. Bxc3 e4 16. Nd2 f5 17. f3 exf3 18. Nxf3 O-O-O {Black has better control over the light squares in the centre.}  ) ( 14. Ne4 $5 {seems a bit more accurate than Iturrizaga's move.} Bd5 15. Qc2 O-O-O 16. a3 Be7 17. Rfc1 {This way, White saves a tempo compared to the game. The position remains double-edged anyway. Here is a sample line:} h5 18. b4 Kb8 19. h4 a6 20. d3 Qe6 $13  ) O-O-O 14. Ne4 Bd5 15. d3 h5 16. h4 Kb8 $13 {The opening has finished. Kings on opposite flanks mean that we have a double-edged affair, which should suit an ambitious black player perfectly. Nakamura proceeded to outplay his opponent instructively in the next phase of the game:} 17.