ising. I would just like to present some of the key games and ideas, which can serve as a background for my choice.} 7. e4 ( 8. d3 d6 9. Be2 $5 {is a clever move order to prevent the counterplay with ...Nh5-f4. Even in that case, it seems like Black's best bet is to play} e4 $1 {in order to damage White's central structure.} ( {The following game is a perfect example of White's general strategy and the passive kind of position that Black can find himself in if he just plays 'normal' moves.} Re8 10. e4 Ne7 11. Nh4 $1 Ng6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. O-O c6 14. f4 $14 { White's strong center allows him to carry out this important pawn break without any issues.} b5 15. cxb5 cxb5 16. h3 Qb6+ 17. Kh2 Be6 18. a4 a6 19. Qb2 Nd7 20. Rb1 Rab8 21. axb5 axb5 22. Rf3 $36 {1-0 Aronian, L (2799) -Matlakov,M (2728) /Tbilisi GEO 2017 (40)}  ) 10. dxe4 Re8 11. Nd2 Ng4 $1 12. h3 Qh4 13. g3 Qh6 $132 {1/2-1/2 (97) Ding,L (2805) -Aronian,L (2752) Stavanger 2019}  ) d6 8. g3 Nd7 9. Bg2 Nc5 10. Nh4 {White stops the ... f5-break and, if unchallenged, he will simply go for 0-0 and f2-f4 at the right moment. Therefore, Black needs to resort to another pawn break for counterplay:} a6 $1 11. O-O b5 $132 12. d4 $5 ( 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Rd1 {1-0 (32) Robson,R (2682) -Sethuraman,S (2673) Saint Louis USA 2018} ( 15. Nf5 Be6 $15  ) Bg4 15. f3 Be6 $1 $15  ) exd4 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Qd2 Nc6 15. e5 Bb7 16. exd6 Qxd6 17. Qxd6 cxd6 18. Nf5 $11 {½-½ Khairullin,I (2662) -Svidler,P (2739) /Chita 2015}  ) 7. Ng5 {This is the most straightforward reply. White wins a tempo by attacking the pawn and plans to undermine it with f2-f3 next.} ( {It is less clear why White would want to play} 8. Nd4 {since the knight moves away from the key e4-square. After} O-O 9. Be2 ( 10. f3 {now comes in an inferior version compared to the main line because we can damage White's pawn structure with} Nxd4 11. cxd4 exf3 12. gxf3 d5 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. h4 f5 $132 { and we get a pretty double-edged position as a result.}  ) Ne5 10. f3 ( {If White p