0. Bxg5 Qg6 $13 {1/2-1/2 (40) Anderson,P (2487) -Stromberg,H (2257) FICGS email 2016}  ) Bb7 {The opening has finished and it is time to create a strategy for the middlegame. Besides the most straightforward plan with} 12. d3 { White has tried many other moves, both in OTB and correspondence chess.} ( 13. Nd4 { is a logical one, when} Qe4 $1 { is an important resource that forces White to trade the queens.} 14. Qxe4 ( 15. d3 $4 {runs into} Nxd4 { which shows one obvious advantage of developing the bishop to b7.}  ) Nxe4 { While the position remains complex, it has to be said that the queen trade has worked in Black's favour since White's attacking potential has all but vanished. Moreover, it becomes easier for Black to exploit White's structural weaknesses in the endgame. The following game is a perfect example of that.} 15. Nb5 Rfc8 16. Rb1 Ne5 17. Rb2 a6 18. Nd4 Re8 19. Nf3 Bc6 20. Nxe5 Rxe5 $17 { 1/2-1/ 2 (82) Hess,R (2581) -Ponomariov,R (2675) Douglas 2019}  ) ( 13. Ng5 {has not been met in practice, but needs to be addressed as the most direct move that White has at his disposal.} h6 14. Nh3 ( 15. Rxf6 hxg5 16. Rf2 Rae8 $11  ) Rae8 15. Nf4 Ne5 16. d3 { and here, just like in the main line, the best way to fight against White's plan to push e4 is} Nfg4 $1 17. e4 f5 {and if} 18. h3 {then} Qh4 $1 19. hxg4 fxg4 $36 { is very unpleasant for White.}  ) ( 13. Rb1 {is a popular move in correspondence chess, although the idea behind it is baffling. Anyway, Black proceeds to centralize his forces, as usual} Rae8 $13 14. Rb5 ( {Here, the engines and correspondence players rate} 15. Rb2 $5 {very highly, although I fail to understand the deep point behind it. It probably has something to do with activating the rook via the second rank at some point, but let's just leave it at that. You won't ever get this in an actual game :)}  ) Ne4 15. Nd4 {1/2-1/2 (41) Antonsen,M (2426) -Thybo,J (2513) Svendborg 2019 Here, it would have been best to prevent ...Nf5 simply with} g6 {and after} 16. d3 Nd6 17. Rb2 Nxd4 18. exd4 {White gets this funny 'Tetris' pawn structure, which I am not sure what to make of. Anyway, Black is doing well after} Nf5 $132  ) Ng4 $1 { This is a very important move to remember.} ( d5 13. cxd5 Nxd5 { is very attractive, with a similar idea as in the main line, but after} 14. e4 Qc5+ {0-1 (19) Harsha,B (2509) -Xiong,J (2709) Chess.com INT 2020 White could have obtained a dangerous initiative if he had played} 15. Rf2 $1 Qxc3 ( Nxc3 16. Bf1 { leaves Black knight stranded on c3.}  ) 16. Qb1 $1 Nf6 17. Bb2 $36 { This is a dream position for White in this variation and it cost him a mere pawn.}  ) 13. e4 f5 14. Bg5 Qe8 15. exf5 ( 16. h3 {is safely met by} fxe4 17. hxg4 exf3 18. Bxf3 Na5 $11  ) h6 ( {There is also nothing wrong with the immediate} Ne3 $5 16. Bxe3 Qxe3+ 17. Rf2 Rae8 18. Raf1 Ne7 $1 $132 { ½-½ (20) Kragten,J (2336) -Bergmanolson,M (2284) ICCF email 2016} ( Rxf5 $2 19. d4 $16  )  ) 16. Bf4 Ne3 17. Bxe3 Qxe3+ {GM Dominguez was very well prepared while Firouzja, probably on his own at this point, made an inaccuracy with} 18. Kh1 $6 {1/2-1/2 (62) Firouzja,A (2728) -Dominguez Perez,L (2758) Chess.com INT 2020} ( {The correct move is} 19. Rf2 {when Black equalizes fully with} Rae8 20. d4 Ne7 21. Nh4 Be4 22. Qc1 Nxf5 23. Ng6 Qxc1+ 24. Rxc1 Rf6 25. Ne5 Re7 $11  ) {Now, Black could have even obtained a more promising position with a precise sequence:} Rae8 $1 19. Rae1 Ne5 $1 20. Bd1 Qf4 21. Nxe5 Rxe5 $1 { It is exactly king's position on h1 that is a problem for White here.} 22. Kg1 Rxe1 23. Rxe1 Rxf5 $15 { In such simple symmetrical positions, an apparently small thing like a weak pawn on a2 can become a big problem.}  *

