{openings101.org} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 Bxc3 {In this chapter, we take a close look at the main line of the 4.e3 system, that is} 6. Qxc3 {In some ways, this position bears similarities to the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian defence. White has won the bishop pair early in the game and is hoping to exploit it in the long run. Black, on the other hand, usually has a better development and more space in the center compared to similar Nimzo positions. Thus, White's main idea is to push d2-d4 and/or b2-b3 in order to provide scope for his dark-squared bishop. Black, on the other hand, should try to counterbalance this with swift central actions that will secure him a strong control on the light squares.} Qe7 {At this point, White have to accomplish the aforementioned goals in several ways.} 7. a3 { is the most popular move. White primarily takes control over the b4-square in order to carry out d2-d4 comfortably.} ( {However, the immediate} 8. d4 {has been trending on the grandmaster level recently. Before it became popular, I have faced it as Black several times in an online blitz against GM Strikovic, one of the English opening specialists and pioneers of this line, and always wondered why it was merely a sideline. Well, it is not anymore! Super-GMs like So, Duda, and Mamedyarov have played it quite successfully with White, so we need to take this move seriously. My suggestion is to answer with a rare} e4 $5 { This, as we will see, is a strategically ambitious move as we are trying to get some sort of a reversed French defence. By playing this way, we shut down a1-h8 diagonal while also obtaining a space advantage on the kingside. I prefer this setup} ( {over the principled} Ne4 { which allows Black to exploit the weakness of b4-square after} 9. Qd3 exd4 10. Nxd4 O-O 11. Be2 Qb4+ 12. Kf1 { Forcing the opponent's king to abandon castling is no small achievement. However, the key features of the position remain the same. White is looking to activate his dark-squared bishop and put a slow squeeze on Black.} Qe7 13. f3 Nc5 ( f5 $5 { is an attractive move, although Black may later regret not being more flexible with the f-pawn.} 14. Qd1 Nc5 15. Kf2 d6 {1/2-1/2 (23) Caruana,F (2827) -Ding Liren (2804) Batumi GEO 2018} 16. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 17. b4 Ne6 18. a4 f4 19. Ra3 $14  ) 14. Qd2 a5 15. b3 d6 {Black position is rock solid and the strength of the white bishop pair can barely be felt. What I slightly dislike about it, though, is that it is rather static for Black. If White strengthens his position gradually, Black may lose patience and concede some important square, diagonal or a file. So, it is not a position that will be to everyone's taste. Of course, as we can see from the example below, it is well-suited for solid positional players like Sergey Karjakin:} 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Bb2 { } Re8 18. Kf2 Nd7 $1 19. h4 h5 20. e4 Ne5 21. Rae1 a4 22. b4 a3 23. Ba1 f6 $1 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (48) So,W (2780) -Karjakin,S (2773) Saint Louis 2018}  ) {While both knight retreats seem equally reasonable,} 9. Ng1 { is preferred by stronger players. As in the advanced variation of the French defence (with reversed colours) , the plan is to manoeuvre the knight via e2, from where it has several attractive squares, like f4, g3 or c3, depending on what Black does in the meantime.} ( 10. Nd2 { on the other hand, puts some pressure on the e4-pawn and can sometimes be activated via c4-square.} d5 {Now White can develop his dark-squared bishop in several ways.} 11. a3 ( 12. b3 { is another one, preparing to deploy the bishop to a3-f8 diagonal after a4. Black has two ways to meet it:} O-O ( {and} h5 $5 { This is a standard move in the French defence, gaining space on the flank and preparing the rook lift.} 13. a4 ( {White's play in the following correspondence game was confusing.} 14. h3 Rh6 $1 15. Bb2 $6 Bf5 16. a4 { That's the right plan. The previous move was a waste of tempo.} a5 17. Ba3 Nb4 18. c5 $6 { Closing the center also doesn't make much sense because it gives Black a free reign on the kingside.} Nc6 19. O-O-O h4 $15 { 1/2-1/2 (34) Loeschnauer,R (2448) -Glatthaar,M (2455) ICCF email 2020}  ) a5 $1 { This is a standard way to neutralize the dark-squared bishop.} 14. Ba3 Nb4 15. Rc1 h4 $132 {Black dominates on the kingside and it may be the best for White to open the c-file for counterplay with} 16. cxd5 Nfxd5 17. Qc5 Qxc5 18. Rxc5 b6 19. Rc1 f5 $11 { Black is in a good shape here.}  ) 13. a4 a5 14. Ba3 Nb4 15. Be2 c6 { This is a solid approach. Black simply completed his kingside development and secured the centre with his last move. White pieces are a bit cramped now, so he may try to break with f2-f3 at some point. Black is ready for that, as we can see in the main line:} 16. O-O ( 17. c5 { can be ignored since} Bg4 $1 {gives us a strong initiative on the other side of the board:} 18. Bxb4 axb4 19. Qxb4 Bxe2 20. Kxe2 h5 $1 $36 { and White's extra pawn doesn't really matter. Black develops his kingside initiative very quickly:} 21. Qc3 h4 22. h3 Nh5 23. Kd1 f5 24. Kc2 f4 $17  ) ( 17. h3 $5 {prevents the exchange of bishops, so it deserves some consideration. Black is doing well, nevertheless, after} Bf5 18. O-O h5 $13  ) Bg4 {The exchange of light-squared bishops is typically a favourable one for Black in these structures. After} 17. f3 {which was played in the game 0-1 (23) Walker, D (2271) -Adair,J (2450) Chess.com INT 2020,} ( {It was better to opt for a less committal continuation} 18. Bxg4 Nxg4 19. h3 Nf6 20. Rfc1 $11  ) {Black should have opened the e-file at once with} exf3 18. Bxf3 Rfe8 $15  ) ( 12. cxd5 $5 $146 {also makes sense in the light of Black's plan to eventually fortify his centre with ...c6. This exchange weakens the e4-pawn, opens the c-file and gives white pieces more manoeuvring freedom via the c4-square. On the other hand, Black doesn't mind getting a strong outpost on d5.} Nxd5 13. Qb3 { That's White's point. Now Black cannot maintain the outpost as easily as he would like to and the knight is forced to retreat.} Nf6 14. Be2 O-O 15. Nc4 a5 16. Bd2 {The position seems rather balanced. Black can reclaim control over d5-square either with} Nd5 ( {or} a4 $5 17. Qa3 Qe6 $13  ) 17. O-O a4 18. Qa3 Qg5 19. f3 Bf5 $13  ) ( 12. Be2 O-O {actually transposes to 7.Be2 line that is discussed elsewhere in this database.}  ) O-O 12. b4 ( {In a recent grandmaster game, White chose a more modest development scheme:} 13. h3 Be6 14. b3 a5 15. Bb2 Rfe8 16. Be2 {Black is very comfortable and here GM Edouard already started playing for an advantage with} a4 $1 17. b4 dxc4 ( Na7 $5 { preparing to eventually transfer the knight to b5, also looks good.}  ) 18. Nxc4 Nd5 19. Qc2 f5 $13 { 0-1 (26) Studer,N (2580) -Edouard,R (2649) Europe Echecs INT 2020}  ) Qd8 $1 { This backward move can easily fall under the radar, but it is a very important part of Black's strategic puzzle. White was threatening to attack black knight with 11.b5 and this move allows us to preserve both the piece coordination and control over d5-square as the knight can now retreat to e7.} 13. Be2 ( {If White proceeds to expand on the queenside with} 14. b5 Ne7 15. a4 {then we continue} Nf5 16. Be2 Re8 17. O-O Nh4 $1 { The knight has travelled across the whole board to land on a very dangerous attacking position. This is a maneuver worth remembering.} 18. Re1 Bg4 19. Bf1 Qd7 $36  ) ( {In another game, GM Navara tried to open the center prematurely with} 14. Bb2 Ne7 15. f3 $2 { and Black punished it with a help of a clever tactic:} Re8 $1 16. fxe4 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Nf5 $1 18. O-O-O Rxe4 $17 { 1/2-1/2 (61) Navara,D (2740) -Nguyen, T (2556) Czech Republic 2019}  ) Re8 14. b5 Ne7 15. O-O Ng6 ( {As usual, Black can also consider exchanging a pair of bishops with} Bg4 $5 16. Bxg4 Nxg4 17. h3 Nf6 18. a4 Nf5 $13  ) 16. cxd5 Nxd5 17. Qb3 c6 $132 { Black is ready for a full-scale attack with ...Qg5, ...Nh4, ...Re6, etc. White's counterplay on the queenside is too slow, so he needs to counterattack in the centre with} 1