2) -Liang,A (2590) Saint Louis 2019}  ) 11. Ne2 h4 12. Nf4 a5 $1 { This is a very convenient way to 'protect' d5-pawn.} 13. a3 ( 14. cxd5 Nb4 15. Bc4 Qd6 $15  ) Qd6 14. h3 Rh6 $1 { While it was still possible to castle, this thematic rook-lift is even more ambitious. The rook becomes more useful on the sixth rank than on f8 while the king is still perfectly safe on e8. The position remains complex, but I see no reason why Black should feel inferior; on the contrary. Below are some sample lines:} 15. Bd2 ( 16. a4 Nb4 17. Ba3 Qe7 18. Nxd5 Nfxd5 19. cxd5 Nxd5 20. Bxe7 Nxc3 21. Bg5 Rh5 22. Bf4 Nd5 $11  ) ( 16. Be2 Bf5 17. O-O $6 dxc4 $1 18. bxc4 g5 $17  ) Ne7 $13  ) ( {White have also tried} 8. b3 { opening the long diagonal for the bishop at once. However, this natural move has a surprising drawback; if Black plays his cards right, the bishop will not reach b2 any time soon!} d5 9. d4 ( 10. cxd5 $6 Nxd5 11. Qb2 { Fianchettoing the queen is an unusual way to justify b2-b3. It was played in the game ½-½ (47) Kovalenko,I (2657) -Karjakin,S (2753) St Petersburg RUS 2018 Here, the strongest continuation is} Bg4 $15 12. Bb5 ( 13. Be2 O-O-O $5  ) Bxf3 13. gxf3 O-O-O $1 14. Bxc6 bxc6 $17  ) exd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 c5 12. Qf4 ( 13. Qb2 {is less principled, but safer than the main line. After} O-O 14. Be2 dxc4 15. bxc4 {I would suggest a slight improvement over the game ½-½ (58) Khismatullin,D (2619) -Kryakvin,D (2588) Sochi 2019} Bd7 $1 $146 16. O-O ( 17. Qxb7 Rfb8 18. Qc7 Ne8 19. Qf4 g5 $1 20. Qg3 Qf6 $19 { and here we have one instance where the main downside of the early b2-b3 gets exposed.}  ) ( 17. Bf3 Bg4 $1 $15  ) Bc6 17. f3 Nd7 18. e4 ( 19. a4 f5 $15  ) Rfe8 $1 19. Bf4 Nf8 $132  ) g5 $1 {The star move! This pawn sacrifice provides Black with plenty of counterplay since white queen, which has already made four out of eleven moves, will need to move some more whereas all of her remaining pieces are stuck in their initial squares.} ( {The main alternative} O-O 13. Bb2 d4 {appeals much less to me, in the view of} 14. O-O-O $1 dxe3 {1/2-1/2 (40) Svidler,P (2753) -Navara,D (2741) Biel 2018} 15. Bd3 $5 $146 exf2 16. Qxf2 $36 { If we compare the suffering that Black will need to endure for one pawn in this kind of position with the pleasure of having the initiative without a pawn in 11...g5 variation, I think that it should be a no-brainer why I chose the latter.}  ) 13. Qxg5 Rg8 14. Qf4 Nh5 {Precision is needed.} ( Rg4 $2 {is the wrong way to go about it since after} 15. Qf3 Qe5 16. Rb1 Bf5 17. Bb2 d4 18. Rd1 O-O-O 19. Bd3 $16 { White fully consolidates and remains with an extra pawn. 1-0 (54) Gorodetzky, D (2449) -Erenberg, A (2396) Petah Tikva 2019}  ) 15. Qh6 Qe5 $36 { That's the tactical point that I mentioned in the introduction to 7.b3. This tempo on the rook is very important and it gives Black a dangerous initiative.} 16. Rb1 Rg6 $1 {Sidelining the queen even more and preparing to bring the knight into the attack. At this point, we don't really count the pawns, it is the white king that we are after!} 17. Qxh7 Nf4 ( Nf6 $5 $146 {is also possible, so that after} 18. Qh8+ Rg8 19. Qh4 Bf5 20. Bb2 d4 21. Rd1 {we get a position that is very similar to Gorodetzy-Erenberg above, with a crucial difference that the queen is placed clearly worse on h4 than on f3, so White still struggles with his development. Black can either force a draw with} Rg4 ( {or play for more with} O-O-O $5 $13  ) 22. Qh3 Rg6 23. Qh8+ Rg8 $11  ) 18. cxd5 ( 19. Bb2 d4 $40 {is just bad for White}  ) Bg4 $1 19. h3 $1 {The only move that keeps the fragile balance.} ( 20. Bb2 $2 {was already a losing mistake in the key game 0-1 (54) Paravyan, D (2634) -Tsydypov,Z (2529) Khanty-Mansiysk RUS 2018.} Qxd5 21. Bb5+ ( 22. Qh8+ Kd7 23. Bb5+ {also fails to save White due to} Rc6 $1 24. Qxa8 Nxg2+ 25. Kf1 Nxe3+ 26. fxe3 Qf3+ 27. Kg1 Qxe3+ 28. Kf1 Bh3#  ) Ke7 22. Qh4+ Ke6 $19 { and White is losing a lot of material. For example:} 23. exf4 Qe4+ 24. Kd2 Qxf4+ 25. Ke1 Qb4+ $1 26. Kf1 Be2+  ) Bh5 $1 20. Bb2 Qxd5 21. Qh8+ Kd7 22. Bb5+ Rc6 23. Qxa8 Nxg2+ 24. Kf1 Nxe3+ 25. fxe3 { If you compare this position to a similar one in 19.Qh8+ line, you will realize that it was necessary to insert 18.h3 to avoid Bh3# at the end of that line. Now, Black can only force a perpetual:} Qxh1+ 26. Kf2 Qf3+ 27. Kg1 $11  ) ( 8. Be2 {is a relatively rare but clever move order. I would suggest that we play} O-O ( {instead of the more common} d5 {when White is trying to get a favourable version of the 7.b3 line with} 9. d4 exd4 ( e4 $6 10. Ne5 $1  ) 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 c5 12. Qf4 O-O ( g5 {doesn't work with the bishop already on e2.} 13. Qxg5 Rg8 14. Qf4 Rxg2 15. cxd5 $16  ) 13. b3 { White has side-stepped the ...g5 line, so now he can freely develop his bishop to b2.} Rd8 14. Bb2 d4 $6 ( {Objectively speaking, Black is better off playing} Be6 { This position is maybe only marginally better for White, so it is fully playable for Black. But it is the kind of position that White wanted to get in the first place and I see no reason to allow this if we have a better alternative (see 7...0-0 8.d4 e4!?) .}  ) 15. O-O-O $16 { 1/ 2-1/2 (47) Xiong,J (2710) -So,W (2772) Saint Louis 2021}  ) 9. d4 e4 $5 { Similarly to 7.d4 line, I firmly believe that this type of position is more promising for Black than both 7...d5} ( {and} exd4 10. Nxd4 Ne4 11. Qd3 {which transposes to 7.d4 Ne4 line, discussed previously in this chapter.}  ) 10. Nd2 {The only sensible move now that Ng1-e2 maneuver is not possible.} ( 11. Ne5 {is slightly suspicious in the view of} Nd8 $1 12. h3 h5 13. c5 d6 14. cxd6 cxd6 15. Nc4 b5 16. Na5 {Black obtained a strong outpost on d5 in ½-½ (23) Gierden,H (2370) -Alfaro de Hombre,J (2309) ICCF email 2019 and perhaps it was best to immediately take advantage of it with} Nd5 $146 17. Qc2 Bd7 $132  ) d5 { This type of position should already be very familar to us from the analysis of 7.d4 e4 variation. Black's general plan is to secure d5-square and eventually