5 {which, as we shall see, leads to a sharp game.} ( O-O $5 {is a more solid approach, completing our development and leaving white queen exposed on d4. Since we didn't play ... c5, White's most principled reply is} 11. c5 { } ( 12. cxd5 {just helps Black mobilize his pieces:} Rd8 13. Bc4 Nxd5 {and White may have to already play for a draw with} 14. Bxd5 Be6 15. Qb4 Qxb4+ 16. axb4 Rxd5 17. Bd2 $11  ) ( 12. Bd2 $5 { has, surprisingly, never been tried over the board, but it is virtually the main move in correspondence chess. White's idea can be seen in 11...c5 line. Instead, I would suggest that we play} Rd8 ( {After} c5 13. Qh4 Rd8 14. cxd5 Rxd5 15. Bc3 { White has accomplished his main goal. Black is still doing fine considering his lead in development and piece activity, but I still prefer 11...Rd8 which is more challenging for White.}  ) 13. Bb4 Qe8 14. c5 {White will have to play this move sooner or later.} ( {For example,} 15. Be2 b6 $5 16. c5 Ne4 17. O-O a5 18. Bc3 f6 19. cxb6 $5 ( 20. b4 {leads to big simplifications:} axb4 21. axb4 bxc5 22. bxc5 Nxc3 23. Qxc3 Bf5 $11  ) c5 20. Qd1 Qc6 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (20) Ludgate,A (2451) -Lubas,J (2228) FICGS email 2021}  ) Ne4 { The knight can assume this powerful outpost only after White has pushed the pawn to c5. Its presence on e4 counterbalances White's control over the dark-square complex in the centre. In a recent grandmaster game, Black kept the balance comfortably.} 15. Bd3 ( 16. Be2 a5 17. Bc3 Qf8 18. Rc1 c6 19. f3 {We can always make the following trade:} Nxc3 20. Rxc3 Bf5 21. Kf2 Re8 $11 {with a very solid position for Black in ½-½ (80) Jonckheere,P (2381) -Fischer,W (2523) ICCF email 2012}  ) Bf5 16. O-O a5 17. Bc3 f6 18. Rad1 Bg6 $11 { 1/ 2-1/2 (31) Strikovic,A (2461) -Saric,A (2538) San Cristobal de la Laguna 2021}  ) ( 12. b4 $6 { is too weakening with such a lag in development. In the following game, Black showed exactly how to punish this move.} dxc4 $1 13. Bxc4 Rd8 $15 14. Qf4 $2 a5 $1 15. b5 Nd5 16. Bxd5 R