{openings101.org} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 {In this chapter, we examine the variation} 4. e4 { which has gained in popularity significantly in recent years, mostly because Magnus Carlsen and his recent World championship challenger, Ian Nepomniachtchi have employed it with decent success on several occasions. It is one of the few variations that completely stops Black from achieving the 'open' reversed Sicilian type of position with ...d7-d5. This is, perhaps, its greatest strength because black players need to shift their mindset from playing an open or semi-open middlegame to handling a more closed, manoeuvring type of game after 4.e4. Objectively speaking, though, this variation should not pose a big challenge from an opening point of view if Black is well prepared. My main suggestion is to play} Bb4 { which is the most solid continuation here. In principle, it is better to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain before pushing ...d6, although it is fair to ask why would we play like this} ( {if we can put the bishop on a more promising diagonal with} Bc5 { ? The answer is that in this case, White opens up the centre with a help of a thematic tactic} 5. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 6. d4 {and after} Bb4 7. dxe5 Nxe4 8. Qf3 $1 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ba5 10. Bf4 O-O 11. O-O-O $1 {we reach an unusual position with small margins for error on both sides. Somehow, though, it's been Black who struggled more in this position in practice, which probably indicates that it is better to look for alternatives on move 4. Here is a recent example:} Qe7 12. Kb2 Rb8 $1 13. Qe3 $1 b5 14. c5 b4 15. c4 $13 {1-0 (44) Nepomniachtchi,I (2784) -Xiong, J (2709) Chess.com INT 2020}  ) ( {That said, Black can also keep the bishop closed in and play} d6 $5 { This is an interesting line to get a sharper position than in 4...Bb4 line. Black would like to fight for d4-square with ...Bg4, and we typically get a KID-type of structure. White's most natural reply is} 5. d4 ( 6. h3 { prevents the bishop sortie, but it is a slight waste of time. Black can now fully adopt the KID strategy by playing} g6 7. d4 exd4 8. Nxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O { A similar position exists in KID opening theory, although there White has a much more useful Be2 instead of h3 on the board. Here, White needs to play} 10. Bd3 { to overprotect the vulnerable e4-pawn. However, this leaves the d4-knight vulnerable in turn and we can exploit it by playing either} Nd7 ( {or even by tactical means:} d5 $5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nxd4 {and if White captures the pawn with} 13. Bxg6 fxg6 $1 14. Bxd4 {then} Qg5 $44 { provides us with enough compensation.}  ) 11. Be2 ( {In the event of} 12. Nxc6 {Black obtains good queenside counterplay with} bxc6 13. Qd2 a5 14. O-O Nc5 $132  ) Re8 12. O-O Nc5 13. f3 f5 $132 { and White still has issues with the central pawn.}  ) ( 6. Be2 {is pretty benign as Black can simply take control of d4-square with} Bg4 7. d3 g6 8. Bg5 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nd4 10. O-O ( 11. Nd5 Bg7 12. O-O c6 $11  ) Bg7 11. b4 c6 12. Rb1 O-O $13  ) ( 6. g3 { is another rather harmless system since white knight is supposed to be on e2 in the Botvinnik English. On f3, it can always be easily pinned by ...Bg4.} g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. d3 ( 10. d4 $6 Bg4 11. d5 Nd4 $15 12. Qd3 {0-1 (43) Fridman, D (2645) -Tkachiev,V (2636) /Warsaw 2010} Nd7 $17  ) Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nd7 {  This is the standard maneuver, aiming to take full control over d4-square.} 12. Bg2 {½-½ (52) Lisitsin,G-Spassky,B/Moscow 1955/URS-ch} Nc5 13. Rb1 a5 $13  ) Bg4 6. d5 Nd4 7. Be2 ( 8. Be3 Nxf3+ 9. gxf3 { gives White some dynamic options on the kingside (attack on the g-file, f3-f4 break) , but it is a structural concession, after all. Black is generally doing well with natural moves, as in the following correspondence game:} Bd7 10. Qb3 b6 11. O-O-O Be7 12. Rg1 Nh5 13. Ne2 O-O 14. f4 f5 $1 $13 {1/2-1/2 (38) Pirs,M (2575) -Tauscher,K (2492) Remote email 2012}  ) Nxe2 {This is a more flexible of the two possible exchanges.} ( Bxf3 8. Bxf3 { pretty much obliges Black to also play} c5 9. dxc6 bxc6 10. Be3 c5 { in order to keep the strong knight on d4. However, White can play around it with} 11. Qa4+ Qd7 12. Bd1 $1 Be7 13. Qxd7+ Kxd7 14. Ba4+ $36 { which leads to an unpleasant endgame for Black, as in the game ½-½ (37) Cuenca Jimenez, J (2523) -Barkhagen,J (2427) Sweden 2020}  ) 8. Qxe2 {As a result of the early opening sequence, White has obtained a central wedge at the expense of the bishop pair. In such positions, White usually still keeps a slight advantage, even if only an academic one, since the closed centre and his extra space easily neutralize the opponent's bishops. Nevertheless, the black position has a lot of hidden potential as KID-type positions naturally do. From Black's perspective, this variation is a good fighting option if you would like to get an imbalanced game. At this point, we have two directions depending on how we would like to develop our dark-squared bishop. Perhaps,} Be7 $5 {in the Old-Indian Defence style is even slightly better} ( {than the KID approach:} g6 9. h3 Bd7 10. Be3 Bg7 { The key difference compared to 8...Be7 is that the bishop cannot support d6-pawn from here. This gives strength to White's c5-break.} 11. O-O O-O ( Qe7 {doesn't solve this issue due to} 12. b4  ) 12. c5 $14 { White is quicker with his queenside play than Black with his on the opposite flank, which gives him an easier game.}  ) 9. h3 Bd7 {At this point, White can try several plans, so let us take a look at them:} 10. O-O ( 11. a4 $5 { was played in the game 1-0 (41) Van Foreest, J (2610) -Gumularz, S (2495) Teplice 2019, when I would suggest that we simply follow the plan from the main line:} O-O 12. a5 a6 13. O-O h6 $1 { and if} 14. Ra3 { it is important to play the prophylactic} Rb8 {before launching kingside counterplay} 15. b4 ( 16. Rb3 b5 $5 17. axb6 cxb6 $132  ) Nh7 16. b5 f5 17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Nd2 Qe8 $132  ) ( 11. c5 $5 $146 { has not been tried before, but that should not stop us from examining thi