{openings101.org} 1. c4 ( 2. e4 c5 3. Nf3 Nf6 {This is the Nimzo-Rubinstein variation of the Sicilian. The main lines goes:} 4. Nc3 d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5+ {which is the same position as the main line in this database only with Nc6 included and colours reversed.}  ) e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4 {This active variation doesn't enjoy such a great reputation for White. The idea is to play the reversed Nimzo-Rubinstein variation with an extra tempo (see 1.e4 c5 above) , but it hardly promises White anything special; in fact, it is usually Black who manages to get a more promising position out of the opening, as we will see shortly.} exd4 ( {The alternative} e4 $5 { is quite interesting, too. With ...Bb4 next, we are trying to get the Nimzo-indian type of position with the pawn on e4, which cannot be a bad deal.} 5. Nd2 ( 6. Ng5 $6 {is a worse way to attack the e-pawn because the knight becomes misplaced on g5 after} Bb4 { and if White tries something radical like} 7. d5 ( 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 d5 $17 { is a great version of the familar type of position from Chapter 7.}  ) Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Na5 9. Qd4 { then we have} c5 $1 10. Qxc5 h6 11. Nh3 d6 12. Qd4 b6 $17  ) ( 6. Ne5 {is a little better, even though after} Bb4 7. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {Black can still try to get an edge with} dxc6 $5 ( bxc6 $11  ) 9. Ba3 ( 10. Bg5 $6 h6 11. Bh4 e3 $1 $17  ) b6 10. e3 h5 $132  ) Bb4 6. e3 ( 7. Ndb1 $5 { is an interesting way to prevent Black from doubling the pawns on the c-file, although in general, knight's manoeuvre from g1 to b1 doesn't inspire too much confidence. After} d5 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3 dxc4 $1 10. d5 Ne7 11. Qa4+ {0-1 (36) Claesen,P (2403) -Gharamian,T (2518) Belgium 2007} c6 $5 $146 12. dxc6 Nxc6 $15 {White is still trailing behind in development and also needs to spend time returning the pawn, so Black should have better chances.}  ) Bxc3 7. bxc3 d6 { Now we have a typical Nimzo-Indian pawn structure. However, the important difference is that our e4-pawn limits White's options in the centre and on the kingside significantly.} 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O {This is by far the most common move here, and the fact that Botvinnik played it means that it cannot be bad.} ( {However, a more modern treatment} 10. g4 $5 { deserves serious attention. In positions with a closed centre, grabbing space on the flanks is highly valued. White will castle queenside and try to build up a kingside attack, so we should get ready for that.} Qe7 11. h4 Nd7 $1 { This is the key idea. We should try to immediately exploit White's lag in development by preparing the f5-break.} 12. g5 ( 13. Qc2 f5 14. gxf5 $2 Nf6 $1 $17  ) f5 13. Ba3 {White has no time to waste, the king should be evacuated to the queenside. We have a good plan against that, too.} b6 $1 14. Qc2 Na5 15. O-O-O c5 $13 { Black has played fully according to Nimzowitsch's rules of the blockade in such positions, limiting White's pawn centre and his bishops. The position remains rich and complex.}  ) Bf5 $1 { This move is more accurate} ( {than} Re8 {which was played in the original game. The ex-World champion skillfully took the initiative with} 10. f3 $1 exf3 11. Bxf3 Rxe3 12. Nb3 $36 {1-0 (32) Botvinnik, M-Ragozin,V Leningrad 1940 and if Black takes another pawn} Rxc3 {then} 13. Bg5 $1 Rxc4 14. Qd2 $40 {  becomes highly unpleasant for him.}  ) 10. f3 ( {Alternatively, White could create something on the queenside with} 11. Ba3 Re8 12. c5 d5 13. Rb1 b6 14. Qa4 Ne7 15. c4 Ng6 $132 { when we get a more double-edged type of position, which, naturally carries some risks for the white king.}  ) exf3 11. Bxf3 Bg6 12. e4 Re8 { The main difference compared to Botvinnik-Ragozin is that here our bishop is on the right diagonal, exerting pressure on the e4-pawn.} 13. Re1 Na5 14. Ba3 Nd7 $11 { This might be a generous evaluation since most people would probably take Black in this position. White's centre is rather high-maintenance.}  ) 5. Nxd4 Bb4 {At this point, White has several developing schemes. In recent years,} 6. g3 { has become the most popular one, and probably for a good reason. The Catalan approach makes the most sense from a positional point of view.} ( 7. Bg5 {used to be the main move for a long time, but it has been practically abandoned by strong GMs in recent years. This pin is not problematic for Black and he often gets a slight positional edge after the exchange on c3.} h6 8. Bh4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 O-O ( {In general, Black solves the pin issue with the following manoeuvre} Ne5 { but it is important to remember that it is slightly premature to do it before castling because of} 10. f4 $1 Ng6 ( Nxc4 $2 11. e4 $16 { Vakhidov, T-Ajapbergenov,A/ Bishkek zt 1993}  ) 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. g3 { and now we get the type of position that is examined in the main line, only with an awkward knight on g6. Karpov addressed this issue immediately in the following game, but it cost him a couple of tempi and White managed to build up a decent position in the meantime.} Nf8 $5 13. Bg2 Ne6 14. e4 d6 15. O-O O-O 16. Qd2 Nc5 17. Rae1 $11 { 1/2 (21) -1/2 Kramnik,V-Karpov,A/ Las Palmas 1996}  ) 10. e3 {White is virtually forced to play this modest move} ( {since} 11. f3 { is strongly met by} Re8 $1 { which prevents 10.e4 tactically. White could still try to make it work with} 12. Bf2 ( 13. e4 $4 {is refuted by a thematic tactical shot} Nxe4 $1 14. Bxd8 Nxc3+ 15. Kd2 Nxd1 $19  ) Ne5 13. e4 {0-1 (47) Singh,R (2299) -Gopal,G (2327) Hyderabad 2005 but here Black has a powerful series of pawn breaks that destroy white center:} c5 $1 $146 14. Nb5 ( 15. Nc2 {is met by} b5 $1 16. cxb5 d5 $1 17. Bxc5 Bb7 $40  ) d5 $3 { Pawn powerplay at work!} 15. cxd5 a6 16. Na3 {Here, Black crowns his strategy with a dangerous pawn sacrifice:} Nxd5 $1 17. Qxd5 Nxf3+ 18. Kd1 Qf6 $1 19. Kc2 Be6 $40 { White army is in complete disarray, which allows Black to conduct a powerful attack.}  ) Ne5 {This is a more appropriate moment to play this move since f2-f4 is not an issue any more.} 11. Nb5 { This is perhaps the only way for White to keep the balance. Anyway, it looks like the most principled move here.} ( 12. f4 {is clearly inferior to 8...Ne5 9. f4 version of this idea because after} Ng6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 { White has issues with the backward e-pawn.}  ) ( {GM Efimenko instructively punished the slow} 12. f3 { with} Ng6 13. Bf2 c5 $1 14. Nc2 d5 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Qd2 { and now the key move is} Nb6 $1 17. Qxd8 Rxd8 18. e4 Na4 19. c4 {White never got a chance to consolidate his forces after} f5 $1 20. exf5 Bxf5 $15 { 0-1 (42) Gorovets,A (2459) -Efimenko,Z (2689) Eilat ISR 2012}  ) ( 12. Be2 {is a bit safer than pushing the f-pawn. However, only Black can be better in the arising positions after he eliminates White's bishop pair advantage with} Ng6 {I once faced} 13. Bxf6 ( {From a structural point of view, it seems even worse to play} 14. Bg3 {which allows} Ne4 15. Qc2 Re8 16. Bd3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 Ne5 18. Be2 d6 19. O-O {1/2-1/2 (48) Rakhmanov,A (2662) -Matlakov,M (2691) Sochi 2016 and here, too} Nd7 $17 { would have been simple and strong, keeping White's attempts to push the central pawns at bay.}  ) Qxf6 14. O-O d6 { Black has an edge because White cannot easily build up a strong pawn center that would compensate for his structural deficiencies.} 15. Rb1 a6 ( {It would have been even better to transfer the knight to c5 more expediently with} Ne5 $5 $15  ) 16. Qd2 Re8 17. Rfe1 Ne5 18. f4 Nd7 19. Bf3 Nb6 20. Qd3 Na4 21. Qc2 Nc5 22. Nb3 Qf5 $1 $15 { 1/2 (50) Semcesen,D (2420) -Kuljasevic,D (2551) Pardubice CZE 2010}  ) ( 12. Bd3 { is very rare, but perhaps not so bad since it discourages 10...Ng6.} d6 13. O-O Nxd3 ( Re8 {could be met by} 14. Bc2 $5 { preserving the bishop pair.}  ) 14. Qxd3 g5 { Black has to unpin this way now, which is a slight concession. Nevertheless, after} 15. Bg3 Qe7 16. f3 Be6 17. e4 Nd7 $132 { White is still slightly on the back foot due to the weak c4-pawn. ½-½ (28) Ludgate, A (2497) -Schwetlick, T (2485) ICCF email 2016}  ) d6 $1 {This move works thanks to an important tactic.} 12. Be2 ( {The point is that} 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Nxc7 {is strongly met by} Nf3+ $1 15. Ke2 Bg4 16. Nd5 Nxh2+ 17. Ke1 Qg5 18. Qd4 Nxf1 19. Kxf1 Be6 $15 {1/2-1/2 (32) Laine,J (2205) -Sherwood,A (2242) ICCF email 2016}  ) Ned7 { A nice way to overprotect the only two vulnerable points in our position. After} 13. f3 a6 14. Nd4 Ne5 15. O-O Ng6 16. Bf2 { White gets to keep the bishop pair while also completing his development, but Black has nothing to complain about after the usual} Nd7 $13  ) ( 7. Nxc6 {is usually played to spoil Black's pawn structure, but such strategy can hardly be effective if Black does the same thing with} Bxc3+ $1 ( bxc6 {would allow White to justify his previous move by continuing} 8. Bd2 O-O 9. g3 Qe7 10. Bg2 Ba6 11. b3 {and if} d5 {then} 12. O-O $1 dxc4 13. Qc2 $13 { gives White a healthy position with full compensation for the pawn.}  ) 8. bxc3 bxc6 { While both sides have a pair of doubled-c-pawns, White's are clearly more vulnerable. Black can solidify his pawns into c7-d6-c5 formation, while White does not have this luxury.} 9. g3 ( {The following variation illustrates this idea the best:} 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 c5 12. f3 d6 13. e4 g5 14. Bf2 Rb8 15. Bd3 Nh5 $15  ) O-O 10. Bg2 Re8 11. O-O Ne4 { A good move that not only threatens to win the pawn but also blocks the g2-bishop.} 12. Be3 {1/2-1/2 (49) Eliseev,A (2260) -Kholmov,R (2435) St Petersburg 1996} Qe7 $146 13. Qd3 Ba6 $15  ) {Black have tried many moves here, some aimed at the c4-pawn, other at the pinned c3-knight, but somehow I prefer to simply complete kingside development with} O-O {and decide what exactly to do on the next move.} ( {If you would like to play something more direct, then} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Na5 { is probably the best bet. White can now defend the c-pawn in three ways:} 8. e4 $5 {Nepo's move is the most ambitious. White builds a strong centre even if it means that he will have to sacrifice the c4-pawn later.} ( 9. Qd3 O-O ( {Another way we can utilize knight's position on the rim is to neutralize the Catalan bishop with} b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Nxb7 {White has to play carefully to keep the balance:} 12. Bg5 O-O 13. Nb5 $5 { We've already seen this motif in 6.Bg5 variation.} Nc5 14. Qf3 Nce4 15. Qxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxd8 Rfxd8 $11  ) 10. Bg2 d6 11. Nb3 $1 Nc6 12. O-O Re8 {White can now improve his pawn structure with} 13. c5 {but that shouldn't deter Black from developing counterplay in the center:} Bg4 14. Re1 Ne5 $132 {1/2-1/2 (30) Almarza Mato,C (2103) -Pruell,L (2264) ICCF email 2021}  ) ( 9. c5 {is slightly premature here in the view of} b6 10. cxb6 axb6 11. Bg2 Bb7 $15 { which works better for Black compared to a similar position in the 8.Qd3 line because of the semi-open a-file. In the following game, White tried to keep things more complex by avoiding the bishops trade with} 12. f3 {but it didn't change the evaluation of the position as better for Black.} O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. g4 Nc4 15. Nf5 d5 16. g5 Nd7 17. Qe1 Nc5 $17 {1/2-1/2 (26) Carow,J (2437) -Fischer,D (2318) Neustadt an der Weinstrasse 2020}  ) O-O ( {It is not advisable to take the pawn because White gets a serious initiative with} Nxe4 $6 9. Bg2 $1 ( {but, of course, not} 10. Qe2 $2 O-O $19  ) Nc5 10. O-O O-O 11. Nb3 Naxb3 12. axb3 d6 13. b4 $36  ) 9. f3 d6 10. h4 $5 { This is much more consistent with White's general strategy in this line} ( {than} 11. Nb3 Nc6 12. c5 $6 {which enables Black to annihilate white center with} d5 13. exd5 Nxd5 $17 { 1/2-1/2 (53) Maljutin,E (2420) -Arbakov,V (2490) Moscow 1997}  ) Be6 $1 $132 { Black needs to act quickly, otherwise he could get squeezed.} 11. h5 ( 12. c5 Bc4 13. cxd6 cxd6 $132  ) h6 12. g4 {White has managed to create some concrete threats on the kingside, so Black needs to be a bit careful now.} Nd7 { 1/2-1/2 (39) Nepomniachtchi, I (2784) -Giri, A (2764) chess24.com INT 2020} ( {I would be more inclined to overprotect my kingside with} Nh7 $5 $146  ) {At this point, White should just accept that he is losing a pawn and focus on the kingside attack with} 13. Kf2 Bxc4 14. Rg1 $44 { Black has counterplay with ...Qh4+ and ...d5, so it's a rather complicated position.}  ) 7. Bg2 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Ne5 { I am slightly more in favour of this way of attacking the c-pawn than ...Na5. This time around, White cannot afford to play anything but} 9. c5 ( 10. Qb3 $6 { is an awkward way to defend the pawn and it was duly punished in the following game:} d6 11. O-O Nfd7 12. a4 Nc5 13. Qa2 a5 14. Nb3 Nxb3 15. Qxb3 Rb8 $15 { White was without counterplay in a suspicious position. 0-1 (42) Kryvoruchko,Y (2612) -Karjakin,S (2732) / Alushta 2008 (42)}  ) Qe7 10. Nb3 Rb8 { This is the most natural way to complete Black's development, preparing ...b6, ...Bb7, etc. So far, White have responded exclusively with 11.0-0, but the critical move seems to be} 11. e4 $1 $146 ( {After} 12. O-O b6 {Black solves all his opening problems if he ever had any. Let us look at White's most interesting responses.} 13. cxb6 {This is the safest one.} ( 14. Qd4 {was the choice of GM Strikovic in one of our blitz encounters: 0-1 (63) lestri (2378) -crotexan2210 (2476) Internet Chess Club 2018. Black has many good options and the engine indicates that} h6 $5 { is the most accurate one, limiting activity of the dark-squared bishop.} 15. Ba3 bxc5 16. Nxc5 d6 17. Nd3 Nxd3 18. exd3 Bb7 $15  ) ( 14. Re1 { is an inspired pawn sacrifice which, however, has been refuted:} bxc5 15. f4 Nc4 16. e4 d6 17. Qe2 Ba6 $1 18. Na5 Qe6 $1 {This is the key move.} 19. f5 Qe5 20. Nc6 Qxc3 21. Nxb8 Rxb8 $17 { As a result of this, more or less, forced sequence, Black has won two pawns for the exchange and had better chances due to much more active pieces. 1-0 (63) Seirawan,Y (2630) -Van Wely,L (2635) Elista 1998}  ) ( 14. f4 Nc6 15. e4 $5 {also deserves an honourable mention, with the following possible line:} Nxe4 16. Re1 f5 17. Ba3 Bb7 18. Nd2 Na5 $13  ) axb6 14. Re1 Re8 15. a4 Bb7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (38) Voetter,H (2121) -Papenfuss,I (2249) GER email 2012}  ) a5 $1 {Among several reasonable replies, this one stands out as the most appealing one. Instead of addressing the f4-e5 threat, Black adds more fuel to the fire as his ...a5-a4, ...Qxc5 threat is just as strong.} ( d6 $5 12. cxd6 cxd6 13. O-O Be6 $11 { is just fine for Black if you are looking to play something simple.}  ) ( b6 {on the other hand, makes less sense here than in 11.0-0 line. White can obtain a more pleasant position with} 12. f4 Nc4 13. O-O d6 14. Qd4 Ba6 15. c6 Rbd8 16. Re1 $14  ) 12. O-O ( 13. f4 {would be well met by} Nc6 $1 14. e5 a4 $132  ) a4 13. Nd4 Qxc5 14. Qxa4 d6 $11 { Black should be happy with the opening outcome. His superior pawn structure will be an asset in virtually all endgames.}  *

