{openings101.org} 1. c4 ( 2. e4 c5 3. Nf3 d6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Nc6 ( g6 {The Dragon variation} 7. Be3 Bg7 8. f3 O-O 9. Qd2 Nc6 10. O-O-O Bd7 $6 ( d5 {is the main move.}  ) 11. g4 $40  ) 7. Be2 e5 {The Boleslavsky variation} ( e6 8. O-O Be7 9. Be3 O-O 10. f4 a6 11. a4 Qc7 {Scheveningen tabiya - White to move.} 12. Kh1 Re8 13. Bf3 Rb8 14. Qd2 Bd7 15. Nb3 b6 16. g4 Bc8 17. g5 Nd7 18. Qf2 Bf8 19. Bg2 Bb7 $13 {0-1 (42) Karpov,A (2720) -Kasparov,G (2700) Moscow 1985}  ) 8. Nf3 ( 9. Nb3 {is slightly inferior to Nf3 since the knight is not placed too well on b3.} Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Be3 Be6 12. Bf3 ( 13. Qd2 a5 $1 $132  ) a5 $132  ) ( 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {isn't considered to be principled here.}  ) {It looks to me like White can play for an advantage here.} h6 ( {or} Be7 9. Bg5 O-O 10. O-O Be6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nd5  ) 9. O-O Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. h3 Be6 12. Bf1 $13 Nb8 $5 13. b3 Nbd7 14. a4 a6 15. Nd2 Rc8 16. Bb2 Qc7 17. Nc4 Qc6 18. a5 $14  ) e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 {In this chapter, we will focus on variations arising after} 4. d3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {We have a reversed Classical Sicilian position on the board. White can try to use his extra tempo to get a favourable version of the Sicilian in a couple of ways. The most common one is the Scheveningen approach with} 6. e3 {From an opening perspective, Black shouldn't be scared of this system. We simply castle, play ...Be6 and ...f5 as in the regular Scheveningen and we have a good position. It is rather the deeper middlegame that can be an issue if you are not too familiar with typical ideas in the Scheveningen positions. Therefore, I will try to go as deeply as possible into the middlegame territory and explain the key ideas that one should be aware of when playing this variation.} ( {The main alternative is} 7. e4 { which we could name the reversed Boleslavsky variation. The pawn structure in the centre (d3, e4 vs e5 or d6, e5 vs e4 with opposite colours) is called the Boleslavsky structure and is quite typical for the Sicilian defence, being featured heavily in the Classical, Najdorf and Sveshnikov variations. Similarly to the Scheveningen approach with 6.e3, it is safe to say that White doesn't strive for an opening advantage but rather wants to get a type of position that he is familiar with (usually relying on the experience of playing a similar sicilian position with black pieces) . The extra tempo (compare this position with 1.e4 - Boleslavsky variation above) is not of much significance here and Black has three more or less, equally good replies. If I had to choose which one to play, I would probably go for} Nf6 { The main idea behind this retreat, as opposed to 6...Nb6 was correctly pointed out by GM Mihail Marin, as ''leaving the b6-square available for the bishop after ...Bc5". Marin,M: 'La posición es típica para la variante de Boleslavsky de la Siciliana (2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 d6 6.Be2 e5 7.Bb3) , pero con colores inversados. En la Siciliana, se considera que las negras tienen cómodo juego, porlo que el tiempo de mas de las blancas en la Inglesa tendría que ofrecerles buenas posibilidades para mantener la tensión. Sin embargo, cabe decir que las negras tienen la posibilidad de recuperar el tiempo de menos jugando ...Bc5 en una sola jugada, lo que explica porque Grischuk ha dejado la casilla de b6 libre, retirando con el caballo a f6.'} ( {Naturally, then, if we play} Nb6 {it means that after} 8. Be2 { we will not develop our bishop to c5, but rather to a more modest square} Be7 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O {It makes sense to compare this position to a similar one with colours reversed (please refer to 1.e4 - Boleslavsky variation) . We can see that Black is doing well there thanks to the ... a7-a5-a4 attack, highlighting the awkward position of the b3-knight. By the same token, White is doing well in a similar position with an extra tempo here, so we need to play carefully to keep the balance.} Be6 {is better} ( {than} f5 11. exf5 Bxf5 {which allows White to open the centre in his favour with} 12. d4 $1 exd4 ( e4 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 c6 15. a4 $1 $14  ) 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Qd7 15. Bf3 Rad8 16. Re1 $1 $14  ) 11. h3 $5 { This is kind of a clever waiting move, basically transposing into the same position as in the Sicilian Defence with colours reversed, with a semi-useful h2-h3 addition. The main idea is actually to wait for Black to play ...Qd7 so that a2-a4-a5 gains in strength.} ( 12. a4 {shows White's cards prematurely and Black can counter this with} Nd7 $1 $11 13. d4 exd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 c6 { Black is completely fine and even got the upper hand after} 16. a5 Nc5 17. Qe5 Nb3 18. Ra4 Bd6 19. Qh5 g6 20. Qh6 Be5 21. Bg5 Qc7 $15 {1-0 (37) Carlsen,M (2733) -Topalov,V (2780) Morelia/Linares 2008}  ) ( 12. Rc1 {is another decent move, when Black keeps equal chances with} Bf6 { (as in the main line)} 13. Na4 Nxa4 14. Qxa4 Qd7 15. b3 Rfd8 16. h3 a5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (20) Kruse,H (2386) -De Vassal,T (2406) FICGS email 2013}  ) Bf6 { This is the correct move.} ( Qd7 {is inaccurate because} 12. a4 $1 { puts the b6-knight in quite an awkward situation, and} a5 $6 {is just bad due to} 13. Nb5 $16  ) 12. Rc1 Qe7 13. Na4 Nxa4 14. Qxa4 Rfd8 $11 { Black has no problems whatsoever in this balanced middlegame.}  ) ( Nxc3 {is the third decent option for Black. The pawn structure transformation after} 8. bxc3 { favors White slightly. The exchange of knights on c6 (c3 in this case) could hardly be recommended for White in a similar position with colours reversed (see 1.e4) . However, if Black is not too preoccupied with these Sicilian/reversed Sicilian opening subtleties and just wants to get a playable position, then this is a perfectly reasonable choice. We continue with} Bc5 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O $13 {and from this position, the players are pretty much on their own. There are some important differences in this type of position compared to the usual Boleslavsky structure. On one hand, Black cannot use the d4-outpost, while, on the other, White cannot develop his usual play along the c-file. The possibilities on both sides are many and it is hard to give any definite evaluation of the arising positions. Let's examine two examples from the recent super-GM practice.} Qe7 ( Bb6 11. a4 Re8 12. Qc2 Qf6 13. Kh1 $1 h6 {Black's last couple of moves were not bad in themselves, but it's difficult to tell what his plan was. Meanwhile, White had a simple and effective one:} 14. Ng1 Qd6 15. f4 $1 {This strong pawn sacrifice allowed Kramnik to unleash the potential of his pawn centre.} Bxg1 16. Rxg1 exf4 17. d4 $36 { 0-1 (42) Kramnik,V (2777) -Giri,A (2783) Wijk aan Zee 2019}  ) 11. Qc2 Bg4 {I like this pragmatic approach more than Giri's sophisticated manoeuvring. Black didn't have much use for this bishop on the queenside, so this seems like a good way to develop (and later exchange) it.} 12. h3 Bh5 13. Kh1 Rfd8 14. Ne1 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 b5 $1 $132 { ½-½ (60) Kramnik,V (2753) -Nakamura,H (2736) Moscow 2019}  ) 8. Be2 {This used to be the preferred move of Vladimir Kramnik, who made reversed Boleslavsky his pet line a couple of years before he quit competitive chess.} ( 9. h3 { is fairly common prophylaxis even in similar positions with colours reversed (...h7-h6) , but it makes less sense if you are trying to utilize your extra tempo as White.} Bc5 ( {It is even possible to get a fine position with less active} Be7 $5 10. Be3 O-O 11. Be2 Re8 12. O-O Bf8 $13 {(please compare this to a similar position with colours reversed above) .}  ) 10. Be2 ( 11. Be3 {is well met by} Qe7 $1 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Rd8 $11 {when Black obtains full control over the d4-outpost and it is rather White who has to be more careful here.} 14. Rc1 Nd4 15. Bxd4 Bxd4 16. Nxd4 Rxd4 17. Qd2 c5 18. f4 b6 $15 {0-1 (44) Edouard,R (2649) -Wojtaszek,R (2719) Biel 2020}  ) O-O 11. O-O Re8 $1 {An important move so that we can preserve the bishop after} 12. Na4 $5 ( {Black did great in practice after} 13. Be3 Nd4 14. Rc1 c6 15. Na4 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Bd4 17. Qd2 Qd6 18. b4 h6 $15 {0-1 (50) Shinkevich,V (2433) -Tomashevsky,E (2714) Sochi 2018}  ) ( {and} 13. a3 Nd4 14. Bg5 c6 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 $15 {1/2 (67) Jobava,B (2596) -Ivanchuk,V (2710) Rethymnon 2003}  ) Bf8 $13  ) Bc5 { This way, we have virtually neutralized White's extra tempo since in a similar position with colors reversed, the bishop goes to e2 first (here, e7) and then you need to spend another tempo as White to play Be2-c4. Here, we do it in only one move.} 9. Be3 Qe7 $1 { This important move, surprisingly, hasn't been too popular so far. The idea behind supporting the bishop with the queen is to clear d8-square for the rook as a way of fighting for the d4-square.} ( {Most strong players have chosen} Bb6 {instead. However, this seems like a waste of tempo compared to 8...Qe7, since after} 10. h3 O-O 11. O-O Qe7 {White can play} 12. Na4 { and exchange the dark-squared bishop on his own terms. White even has some chances to obtain an advantage, for example:} Rd8 13. Nxb6 axb6 14. Qc1 Nd7 15. d4 $1 $146 ( 16. Qc3 Nc5 17. Rfc1 Ne6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (57) Vitiugov,N (2747) -Grigoriants, S (2542) Moscow 2019}  ) exd4 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 $14  ) 10. Rc1 ( {If White tries to pursue the bishop with} 11. O-O O-O 12. Na4 { it is important not to make any concessions and play} Bd6 $1 13. h3 Rd8 $11 {with a good position. For example:} 14. Rc1 h6 $1 15. Qc2 Nh7 $132  ) {Now we have to play} Bb6 {but White has also lost a tempo on Rc1, so the position is balanced after} 11. h3 O-O 12. O-O Rd8 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (15) Einersen,E (2468) -Sivic,J (2572) ICCF email 2018}  ) ( 7. g3 {is also possible, when White wants to transpose into the reversed Dragon having avoided 4.g3 Bb4, 4.g3 Bc5 and a few other non-d5 variations for Black. This isn't so important for us since we play 4...d5 against 4.g3 anyway, but it could be a useful move order for White. Of course, we could just ignore White's opening subtleties and continue 6...Be7 7.Bg2 Nb6, transposing to the positions that we have discussed previously, but we also have a more ambitious option:} f6 $5 ( Be7 8. Bg2 Nb6 {[%emt 0:00:02] transposes to Chapters 1 and}  ) 8. Bg2 Be6 9. O-O Qd7 { Since White has wasted a tempo on d2-d3 earlier, we now have a genuine Dragon. Now it is in White's best interest to play} 10. d4 {since all other moves could lead to a dangerous position where Black attacks on the kingside as in the normal Dragon with colours reversed. Black responds with} O-O-O $1 {and we get a roughly balanced position after} 11. dxe5 ( {or} 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Nxe5 Qxd4 14. Nd3 Bd5 15. Be3 Qg4 $11  ) Nxc3 12. Qxd7+ Bxd7 13. bxc3 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 fxe5 $11  ) ( 7. Bd2 {is a rare yet notable move. It seems even more principled to go for the sharp queenside castling plan with} f6 $5 {now that White has also committed his bishop to d2.} ( {Somewhat surprisingly, most strong players have opted for the less ambitious} Be7 8. g3 O-O 9. Bg2 Be6 10. O-O Qd7 {which leads to the type of position that we analyzed in previous chapters.} 11. a3 ( 12. Ne4 f6 13. Rc1 a5 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 a4 16. Qc1 Nde7 17. Qb1 Nf5 18. Rfc1 Qf7 19. a3 Nfd4 $15 {0-1 (49) Fedoseev,V (2673) -Kryvoruchko,Y (2702) Novi Sad 2016}  ) a5 12. Rc1 f6 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Qa4 Rfd8 15. Rfe1 Be6 $13  ) 8. g3 Be6 9. Bg2 Qd7 10. O-O O-O-O { and White cannot break with d3-d4 in the centre anymore, so he has to resort to traditionally less successful plans, such as} 11. Nxd5 ( {or} 12. Rc1 g5 13. Ne4 Be7 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 Kb8 $36  ) Bxd5 12. Qa4 Kb8 13. Rfc1 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nd4 15. Qxd7 Nxf3+ 16. Kg2 Nh4+ $1 17. gxh4 Rxd7 $15  ) Be7 ( {There is also nothing wrong with the queenside castling plan:} Be6 $5 7. Be2 f6 8. O-O Qd7 {although these positions are much less explored so people generally don't go for this line. Here is one possible continuation:} 9. a3 O-O-O 10. Nxd5 Bxd5 11. b4 g5 12. Nd2 h5 13. Qa4 ( 14. Bb2 a6 $13  ) a6 14. Ne4 Qe6 15. Rb1 Na7 $13 {I would encourage you to explore this type of position further if it appeals to you.}  ) 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Be6 9. a3 { White can hardly do without this move in the reversed Scheveningen.} ( 10. Bd2 {is likely to transpose to the main line after} Nb6 11. a3 a5  ) ( 10. Nxd5 Bxd5 11. Bd2 { is virtually the only other independent attempt, trying to save a tempo on a2-a3 after} Qd6 12. Bc3 Rad8 13. Qa4 f6 14. Rfd1 Qd7 15. Qc2 {but even here Black can utilize b4-square for} Nb4 $5 16. Qb1 c5 17. a3 Na6 18. b4 $13 {1/2-1/2 (60) Sunye Neto,J (2375) -Timman,J (2625) Rio de Janeiro 1979}  ) a5 10. Qc2 ( {The main alternative is} 11. Bd2 { when it is well known from positions with colors reversed that we should avoid the knight trade with} Nb6 $1 { which makes the bishop a bit clumsy on d2 and potentially strengthens ...g5-g4 pawn attack. Black also has a positional threat in 11...a4, so White has to choose between} 12. Na4 ( {and} 13. b3 f5 14. Qc2 Bf6 15. Rab1 Qe7 { and here White usually reroute the bishop via} 16. Bc1 ( {although} 17. Na4 $5 { is an interesting alternative. As usual, we respond by running away from the exchange with} Nd7 $1 {and if} 18. b4 axb4 19. axb4 {½-½ (34) Bishop,W (2400) -Kudr,R (2384) ICCF email 2021 then} b5 $1 {is a strong counter-attack.} 20. Qxc6 bxa4 $132  ) {Black has two good plans here. Practice has seen} g5 ( {though it is also possible to build the attack more slowly with} Kh8 $5 17. Bb2 Qf7 $13 { and choose the plan depending on what White does.}  ) 17. Na4 ( {White should have followed the good-old principle of countering the flank attack with a central break:} 18. d4 $1 exd4 19. Nb5 $44  ) g4 $36 18. Nd2 Nd7 19. Re1 {1-0 (38) Garcia Gonzales,G-Timman,J (2585) Buenos Aires 1978 Here, I would suggest an improvement over the game above:} Qf7 $5 20. Bf1 h5 21. Bb2 h4 22. d4 e4 $1 $15  ) Nd7 { The exchange avoidance policy is typically the best in these positions because White struggles with his piece coordination a bit when there are more pieces on the board.} 13. Qc2 ( {If White tries to force the issue with} 14. Bc3 Bd6 15. d4 {we have} e4 16. d5 exf3 17. Bxf3 Nde5 $1 18. Be2 ( 19. dxe6 Qh4 $19  ) Bd7 19. dxc6 Bxc6 $15 { and in the resulting position Black has clearly superior pieces.}  ) f5 14. Rab1 { White prepares b2-b4, but this plan has a small tactical drawback that can be exploited with} Kh8 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 e4 $1 { and White cannot take the pawn because of the tactical vulnerability of his queenside pieces. The initiative is firmly in Black's hands.} 17. Ne1 f4 ( Bd6 $5  ) 18. dxe4 fxe3 19. fxe3 Rxf1+ 20. Bxf1 Nce5 $15 {0-1 (41) Hakulinen,E (2350) -Turunen, E (2270) Helsinki 1990}  ) f5 {You can compare this position to the Scheveningen tabiya at the start of this chapter and you will realize that what GM Mihail Marin said is true: 'With reversed colours, this position was rehearsed in the second Karpov-Kasparov match (1985) . White needs to find the optimal way of taking advantage of the fact that, unlike in the Scheveningen, it is his turn to move.' White has tried many moves here, so let us examine them carefully:} 11. Re1 { This is also the most common move in a similar position in the regular Scheveningen. It's useful against certain black replies because it prepares Bf1 (in some cases g3, Bg2) and potentially e3-e4.} ( 12. Bd2 {is also quite common, but it merely transposes to 10.Bd2 line after} Nb6 {etc.}  ) ( 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. e4 {is another reasonable plan, although this can hardly trouble Black. After} Qd7 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Be3 Rad8 $11 { the weakness on d3 is offset by the weakness on e5 and the same goes for d4 and e4 squares. Therefore, the position is roughly balanced.}  ) ( 12. Na4 { I give the word to GM Marin again: "In the Sicilian, this kind of knight move (...Nc6-a5) is not recommended at such an early stage since Black releases the pressure in the centre at a time when he is not well developed. White hopes that the extra tempo entitles him to forget about this warning.''} Qd6 {This is the most natural move here as it stops White's main threat.} ( {However, Black can also afford to ignore Na4-c5 and launch the pawn attack instead:} g5 $5 $36 13. d4 {probably has to be played} ( {since} 14. Nc5 $6 Bxc5 15. Qxc5 g4 16. Nd2 f4 $40 { already looks quite dangerous for White.}  ) {and then} e4 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 c6 16. Nc5 Bxc5 17. Qxc5 Qe7 $15 { gives Black an edge due to the vulnerable e5-pawn.}  ) 13. Rd1 ( {White could also break in the center at once with} 14. e4 Nb6 15. exf5 Rxf5 16. Nxb6 cxb6 17. Be3 b5 $11 {with a fairly balanced position.}  ) Rad8 14. d4 {This is the wrong pawn break.} ( {The other thematic pawn break is more to the point:} 15. e4 Nf4 16. Bxf4 exf4 17. Rac1 {Black holds his own with active play:} Nd4 $1 18. Nxd4 Qxd4 19. Qxc7 Bh4 20. Qxf4 Be7 $1 21. Nc3 fxe4 22. Qxe4 Qxf2+ 23. Kh1 $11  ) e4 {Now we have a reversed French structure where Black is better mobilized and has more realistic chances for a kingside than White for a queenside attack.} 15. Nd2 Bf7 $1 16. Nc3 {With this move White admits a strategic defeat. The alternatives are clearly worse.} ( 17. Nc4 Qh6 18. Ne5 {fails to} Bd6 $1 $19  ) ( {while} 17. Nc5 {runs into} Nf4 $1 18. Bf1 Qg6 $1 $40 {and if White accepts the piece sacrifice} 19. exf4 {then his position collapses after} Nxd4 20. Qc3 Nf3+ $1 21. Nxf3 Rxd1 22. Ne5 Qh5 $19  ) Qh6 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 $15 { 0-1 (55) Van Wely,L (2692) -Karjakin,S (2769) Wijk aan Zee NED 2012}  ) ( 12. Rd1 { was once played by Magnus Carlsen, with an obvious idea to support the central breaks. Black should continue} Kh8 13. Na4 {and now} Bd6 $5 $146 { protects him well from e2-e4.} ( Qd6 {is also fine, but only if Black continues} 14. Bd2 Bg8 $1 ( {instead of} g5 $6 15. d4 $1 e4 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Qxe5 18. Bc4 $36 {1-0 (33) Carlsen,M (2847) -So,W (2770) chess24.com INT 2021}  ) 15. e4 fxe4 16. dxe4 Qg6 17. Rac1 $13  ) 14. Nc5 Bc8 {and if} 15. e4 {then} Nde7 $15 { looks nice for Black.}  ) Kh8 {This neutral and useful move is the best here. Black is not showing his cards yet (with moves such as 11...Bf6/11...Bd6 or 11. ..Qe8/11...Qd7) and sends the ball back into White's court. So, in some sense, being down a tempo compared to the regular Scheveningen isn't such a bad thing here.} 12. Bd2 {Completing development makes the most sense.} ( 13. Bf1 {looks a bit too sophisticated at this stage. Anyway, Black has a good reply in} Bg8 $1 14. Rb1 ( {Trying to force the central break with} 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. e4 {doesn't work well for White with the bishop on f1 because after} Qd6 17. exf5 Rxf5 18. Be3 {Black has a strong exchange sacrifice at his disposal:} Rxf3 $1 19. gxf3 Bd5 $36  ) Qd6 { We have seen this manoeuvre in some similar positions. It worked great for Black in the following game:} 15. Nb5 Qg6 16. Kh1 e4 17. Nd2 exd3 18. Bxd3 Ne5 $40 {0-1 (25) Pap,G (2508) -David,A (2622) Porto San Giorgio ITA 2010}  ) Nb6 { As I already explained previously, this is the standard reply to White's last move (please refer to 10.Bd2 Nb6 line for details) .} 13. b3 Bf6 14. Rab1 Qe7 { This natural developing move comes with a tempo. In addition, we plan to manoeuvre the queen to g6. This allows us to attack comfortably with our pieces and without exposing our own king,} ( {as we would if we played} g5 $5 15. Bc1 g4 16. Nd2 Bg7 17. Bb2 $13 {This is a reasonable plan, of course, by analogy to Karpov-Kasparov game at the beginning of the chapter.}  ) 15. Bc1 ( {White could also contemplate} 16. Nb5 Rac8 17. e4 {when Black can continue with his usual attacking plan, nevertheless:} Qf7 18. Bf1 Qg6 $132  ) Rad8 16. Na4 {This is a standard move, although White doesn't achieve much with it if Black reacts correctly.} ( {Perhaps it is better to keep the knight closer to the centre and continue} 17. Bb2 $5 Qf7 18. Nd2 Qg6 19. Bf1 $13 {with a complex struggle ahead.}  ) Nd7 $1 { This way, we isolate the knight on a4 and bring our own knight a bit closer to the center.} ( Nxa4 $6 {would allow White to obtain counterplay on the b-file:} 17. bxa4 Bc8 18. Rb5 $132  ) ( {whereas} g5 $6 {facilitates White's queenside counterplay:} 17. Nc5 Bc8 18. b4 g4 19. Nd2 axb4 20. axb4 Qf7 21. b5 $36 {Bosboom,M (2385) -Ermenkov,E (2475) /Amsterdam 1988/CBM 009 (1/2, 75)}  ) {After several logical moves} 17. Bb2 Qf7 18. Nd2 Qg6 $36 { we have a position which looks more promising for Black thanks to the attacking potential.}  *

