{openings101.org. In this chapter, we will examine a host of relatively rare 4th moves for White in the 'Four knights reversed Sicilian' tabiya. You may even never get some of these moves in your games, but it is still worth knowing about them so that you can have a comprehensive understanding of the reversed Sicilian. As usual, we will compare and contrast some of the key variations to those that are played with reversed colours in the regular Sicilian Defence.} 1. c4 ( 2. e4 c5 3. Nf3 e6 ( Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 e5 7. Ndb5 d6 {Sveshnikov Sicilian - Caruana variation:} 8. Nd5 $5 Nxd5 9. exd5 Nb8 10. a4 Be7 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Nd7 13. Bd2 a6 14. Na3 a5 15. c3 f5 16. f4 $13 {1-0 (42) Esipenko,A (2603) -Gelfand,B (2655) Skopje 2019}  ) 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Nc3 Qc7 {Taimanov Sicilian} ( {Four knights Sicilian:} Nf6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 Nd5 9. Ne4 Qc7 10. f4  ) ( a6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 d5 9. O-O Nf6 10. Re1 Be7 11. e5 Nd7 12. Qg4 g6 {used to be the main line of the Paulsen Sicilian.}  ) 7. Be3 ( 8. Be2 a6 9. O-O Nf6 10. Be3  ) ( 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bd3 Nf6 10. O-O Be7 11. Qe2 d5 $11  ) a6 8. Qd2 Nf6 9. O-O-O Be7 10. f3 b5 11. g4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bb7 13. Kb1 O-O {Black is typically doing well in practice.}  ) e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. a3 {Among the moves that we will cover in this chapter, this is by far the most common one and it has a fairly decent theoretical reputation. Whites' idea is to prevent moves like 4...Bb4 and 4...Bc5, while in the case of 4...d5 they typically plan to get a favourable version of the Taimanov Sicilian (please compare to 1.e4 above) .} ( {The 'Four knights' setup is pretty flexible, so White has a variety of rare yet decent options here in addition to those that we have already discussed in chapters 6 through 11. Among them,} 5. Qc2 {is the most interesting one. White plans to discourage 4...d5 by tactical means, while keeping an option of transposing to the Taimanov Sicilian with e2-e3 and a2-a3 later. In my view, we can meet this move in two good ways. If we would like to simply equalize, then} Nd4 {is the best option.} ( {It is important to be aware that the usual} d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 {isn't that good here because of an unexpected tactic:} 7. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 8. Qe4 {when White wins a pawn. To be fair, Black can obtain a decent compensation for it after} Nb4 9. Qxe5+ Be7 10. Qe4 g6 11. Qb1 O-O 12. a3 Nc6 13. e3 Bf5 14. d3 Ne5 15. e4 Be6 16. Be2 Nc6 $44 {1-0 (99) Caruana, F (2822) -Karjakin, S (2754) Bucharest 2019, although I am not sure if it is the best idea to enter this kind of position willingly as Black if we have two less committal alternatives.}  ) ( Be7 $5 {seems to be a more flexible choice if we would like to just get a normal game. After} 6. e3 O-O 7. a3 {we can finally play} d5 {since White does not have any tactical tricks with the e5-pawn. And so,} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {leads us to a position that also arises in the 6.Be2 variation of the Taimanov Sicilian, with the only difference that Black does not have the bishop on e6 yet. This gives White some leverage on the light squares, although it is nothing that Black should worry too much about. Let's examine White's options:} 9. Bd3 ( {I would assume that the first question of most people who are new to this position would be: What is White plays} 10. Bb5 { ? The answer is:} Bg4 $1 {This important move allows us to simultaneously defend the e5-pawn and invoke some weaknesses in the white position as compensation for the doubled c-pawns.} 11. Bxc6 Bxf3 12. gxf3 ( 13. Bxb7 {is met by} Nb4 $1 14. axb4 Bxb7 15. O-O Bxb4 $15  ) bxc6 $132 { we have a reversed Rauzer attack-type of structure where White needs to be very careful about his king's safety.} 13. b3 $6 Nxc3 14. dxc3 Qd5 $17 {0-1 (33) Beim,V (2563) -Rublevsky,S (2662) Frankfurt 2000}  ) ( 10. Nxd5 {is the most popular move in this position and perhaps the most obvious way in which White can take advantage of the absence of a black bishop on e6. Nevertheless, after} Qxd5 11. Bc4 ( 12. Bd3 {-8.Bd3}  ) Qd6 12. b4 Bf6 13. Rb1 Rd8 14. O-O Bg4 {Black completes his development easily and gets a perfectly fine position. In Paulsen structures, the backward d-pawn and the square in front of it are quite important, so I believe that the following bishop manoeuvre is also instructive:} 15. Be2 Bh5 $5 16. d3 h6 17. Rd1 {and now that d4-break is kept in check, we might as well take the time to solve the issue of the backward c-pawn with} Ne7 $1 18. Bb2 c6 19. h3 Nd5 $13 {1/2-1/2 (26) Kayser,P (2270) -Mayer,R (2478) ICCF email 2014}  ) ( 10. b4 {is typically not considered as principled because it allows} Nxc3 { when White is forced to recapture with} 11. dxc3 {which shuts down the c-file. That said, this structure has its own perks for White, particularly if Black doesn't react appropriately. I would recommend simple development for starters:} Be6 12. Bd3 {This is a provocative move.} ( {White cannot win the central pawn with the help of} 13. b5 $6 {because of} Na5 14. Nxe5 $4 Bf6 $19  ) ( {In the event of} 13. e4 {we continue} f6 14. Be3 a5 $1 { This is a very important move that provides Black with timely counterplay. White cannot keep the tension in a good way, so he has to play} 15. b5 Nb8 16. c4 {when Black can keep rocking the boat with} c6 $1 17. c5 {1/2-1/2 (55) Le,Q (2706) -Ponomariov,R (2682) Hengshui 2019} {and now} cxb5 $146 18. Bxb5 Nd7 $132 { would provide Black with strong counterplay against the c5-pawn.}  ) f5 13. e4 { Pawns don't move backwards, so White's claim is that now that ...f7-f6 isn't available to Black, his e5-pawn is more vulnerable. While this is true, it is also a fact that} f4 $132 { gives Black a significant space advantage and attacking potential on this side of the board.} 14. Bb2 ( 15. O-O $6 {is already very dangerous because of} g5 $40  ) Bf6 15. c4 ( {White could temporarily stop ...Bg4 with} 16. h3 {but then Black plays} Qe8 $1 17. c4 Qh5 $132  ) Bg4 16. Be2 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Nd4 $11 {1/2-1/2 (35) Koegler,K (2539) -Rook,D (2494) GER email 2015}  ) Kh8 $1 {This is the least committal way to protect the h-pawn, so it should be preferred over the alternatives.} 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Be4 {This is the sharpest move.} ( {I guess that it goes without saying that the only thing that White can get out of the following operation...} 12. Bxh7 $4 g6 13. Bxg6 fxg6 14. Qxg6 Bf5 $19 {... is a losing position.}  ) ( 12. b4 {is a reasonable alternative, when Black goes} f5 13. Bb2 ( 14. b5 $6 {leads to exchanges that are favourable for the better-developed side - in this case, it is Black.} e4 15. Bc4 Qd6 16. bxc6 exf3 17. gxf3 Qxc6 $15 { 1/2-1/2 (20) Agdestein, S (2590) -Sadler,M (2628) Germany 2001}  ) e4 14. Bc4 Qd6 15. Nd4 { Despite having a backward pawn in the centre, this kind of position may be appealing to White because his bishops operate on long diagonals. However, Black can neutralize them fairly easily, as evidenced by the following correspondence game.} Bd7 16. O-O Ne5 17. Be2 Rad8 18. Rac1 c6 19. f4 exf3 20. Nxf3 Nxf3+ 21. Rxf3 Bf6 $11 { 1/2-1/ 2 (22) Anreiter,A (2216) -Ilyin,P (2302) ICCF email 2013}  ) Qe6 12. b4 Bd7 13. Bb2 ( 14. b5 $6 Na5  ) {We are about to enter a forced sequence now:} f5 14. Bxc6 Bxc6 15. Nxe5 Bxg2 16. Rg1 { and here Black can stop White's attack along the g-file in its tracks with} Bf6 ( Be4 $5 { is a bit more complicated, but also playable.}  ) 17. Rxg2 Bxe5 $11 {with a balanced heavy piece middlegame/ endgame in ½-½ (18) Degerhammar,R (2500) -Kubicki,T (2450) ICCF email 2015}  ) 6. Nxd4 exd4 7. Nd5 ( 8. Ne4 {is an alternative which gives Black an additional option} d5 $5 {This is a very interesting pawn sacrifice.} ( c6 {transposes to 6.Nd5 after} 9. Nxf6+ Qxf6  ) 9. Nxf6+ Qxf6 10. cxd5 {0-1 (31) Wagh, S (2246) -Bachmann,A (2599) Chess.com INT 2020} {and now} Bf5 $1 $146 { is the critical move as Black tries to take initiative in the opening.} 11. e4 $1 {is the best defence, otherwise White may get in trouble.} ( 12. Qxc7 Bd6 13. Qxb7 O-O $40 { Being up three pawns is a small consolation when your development is non-existent and your queen is wandering around in the enemy's territory. Such games often end as miniatures.}  ) ( 12. d3 O-O-O $36  ) dxe3 12. Qa4+ Bd7 13. Qe4+ Be7 14. dxe3 {White managed to consolidate to a degree, but we should not give him a break and so} c6 $1 $44 {is the right move.}  ) c6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. e3 {We have a fairly simplified and balanced position, which is what I was referring to as the equalizing option on move 4. Of course, there is still a lot of play left in such positions and we can continue in several ways. Here are two good options:} g6 ( {and} dxe3 $5 $146 10. dxe3 Qg6 11. Qxg6 hxg6 12. Bd2 d6 13. Bc3 Be6 14. Be2 d5 $13  ) 10. Be2 ( 11. Bd3 Bg7 12. O-O O-O 13. Rb1 d5 $5 {If Black wants to equalize directly, this is the most straightfoward way.} 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. b3 Be6 16. Qc7 dxe3 17. dxe3 Qd8 {1/2-1/2 (15) Rivas Maceda,J (2374) -Bennett,C (2368) ICCF email 2015}  ) Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. e4 ( 13. Bf3 d6  ) {and here, too, Black can settle matters in the centre with a thematic break} d5 $1 13. cxd5 ( 14. d3 dxe4 15. dxe4 c5 16. f4 b6 17. Bd3 Bb7 $11  ) cxd5 14. exd5 Bf5 15. d3 Rac8 16. Qb3 Rfe8 17. Bf3 Bf8 $1 18. Bd2 Qa6 $132  ) ( 5. Qa4 { is a very rare move, although it's not as bad as it looks. This queen sortie is aimed at preventing a couple of black options, including 4...d5 due to the pin on c6-knight. We should, therefore, complete our development in some other way, for example:} g6 ( {or} Be7 $5  ) 6. d3 Bg7 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. e3 O-O 10. Be2 Qd8 11. Rc1 d6 12. b4 Ne7 13. O-O f5 $13 {1/2-1/2 (34) Murey,J (2500) -Sokolov,A (2605) Moscow 1992}  ) ( 5. h3 {is another sideline worth mentioning. After} d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 {White can aim for the reversed Sveshnikov with} 7. e4 Ndb4 8. d3 { The point is that the usually preferred continuation 7...Bg4 is not possible here exactly because of White's fourth move. However, worry not, because we have another good option in} Nd4 $5 9. Nxd4 exd4 {which basically transposes to the variation that Caruana revived in the 2018 World Championship match against Carlsen. If we play by analogy to a similar position with colours reversed, then we could get the following continuation:} 10. Nb1 a5 11. Be2 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Nd2 Bd7 $5 $13 { Please compare this position to the game Esipenko-Gelfand at the start of the chapter. The presence of pawn on h3 instead of h2 doesn't make that much of a difference.}  ) ( 5. b3 $6 {is surprisingly suspicious at this point. The fianchetto of the queen's bishop is more appropriate without the knight on c3, as we will see in Chapter 13.} d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bb2 Bf5 $1 $146 {  White is suddenly facing some serious threats along the b1-h7 diagonal.} 8. Nxd5 ( 9. a3 e4  ) ( 9. e3 Ndb4  ) Qxd5 9. e3 Nb4 { and there is no way to repair the light-squared weaknesses.} 10. Bc4 Nd3+ 11. Kf1 Qd6 12. Qc2 Bg6 $17  ) d5 5. cxd5 ( 6. d4 {is an inferior alternative. Black gets a very pleasant endgame by force:} exd4 7. Nxd4 dxc4 $1 8. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 bxc6 { From White's perspective, tripled pawns may seem like weaknesses, but winning any one of them may prove to be a serious challenge. While White is organizing his forces for this aim, Black will centralize his pieces and take control of important central files and outposts. The following variations illustrate this point well:} 10. f3 ( 11. g3 Be6 12. Bg2 Bd5 $1 13. O-O O-O-O 14. Bg5 Be7 15. Rc1 Rhe8 $15  ) Be6 11. e4 Nd7 $1 12. Be3 Nb6 13. Rc1 O-O-O $15  ) Nxd5 6. Qc2 { Most White players go for some version of a reversed Taimanov with this move. Just as in the Taimanov, the main idea behind the queen's early development to c2 is to prevent the opponent from grabbing space in the centre with ...Nxc3 and ...e4.} ( 7. e3 $6 {on the other hand, is suspicious precisely because of that:} Nxc3 8. bxc3 e4 9. Nd4 Ne5 10. Qc2 f5 {And now we have a position that also arises in one of the big theoretical lines of the Four knights Sicilian variation, only with an extra tempo a2-a3 (please compare it to a similar position at the start of the chapter) . Having played and analyzed this variation of the Sicilian Defence extensively myself, I can say that Black typically struggles to equalize, so the only reason why someone would play the same variation with White is to utilize the extra tempo a2-a3. However, unlike most other reversed Sicilian tabiyas that we have covered in this repertoire where the extra tempo either matters to some degree or has a neutral value, in this position the a2-a3 tempo is actually making the white position worse! This is because if White plays} 11. Qb3 ( {Fabiano Caruana tried something different in the following game:} 12. c4 c5 13. Nb5 {1-0 (25) Caruana,F (2822) -Karjakin,S (2773) Saint Louis 2018} {although Black is clearly better with the simple} a6 $146 14. Nc3 Be6 $17 { anyway. Even the piece sacrifice} 15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. Qxe4 {doesn't help him in the view of} Bd6 17. Bb2 Qc7 18. f4 Qc6 $1 $17  ) c5 12. Bb5+ Ke7 { as in the main line of Four Knights Sicilian, there is no 12.Ba3 which forces the opponent's king to assume a worse position on f6. Without that option, White is plain worse, as the following game indicates:} 13. f4 Nf7 14. Ne2 Nd6 $17 {0-1 (45) Minasian,A (2432) -Golod,V (2573) Yerevan ARM 2014}  ) ( 7. e4 { is another attempt to get a Sveshnikov type of position, but in this case, we cannot play 6...Ndb4. Retreating the knight to f6 or b6 would allow White to develop his bishop to b5, so we should attack d3-square from the other side} Nf4 8. d4 {The strong knight should be undermined.} ( 9. d3 {is too timid. Black wins the battle for d4-square very easily by playing} Bg4 10. Be3 ( 11. Bxf4 Bxf3 $1 12. Qxf3 Nd4 $17  ) Bxf3 11. Qxf3 ( 12. gxf3 Ne6 $15  ) Nd4 12. Qd1 c6 13. g3 Nfe6 $15 {and we have something akin to a reversed Sveshnikov: 0-1 (34) Ibragimov, I (2610) -Galliamova, A (2560) St Petersburg 1998 CBM 067 [Ribli]}  ) exd4 9. Bxf4 dxc3 10. Qxd8+ ( {I also slightly prefer black position in the event of} 11. bxc3 Qf6 12. Qd2 Bg4 $15  ) Nxd8 11. bxc3 Ne6 12. Bg3 { This endgame might seem ''drawish'' to less experienced players, but there is surely something to play for on the basis of White's compromised pawn structure. I like} Nc5 $5 { the most.} ( Be7 13. Bc4 O-O $11 {0-1 (46) Flachet,T (2045) -Cornette,M (2418) Sautron 2005}  ) 13. Bxc7 Nxe4 { with a nice risk-free edge in the endgame.} 14. Bd3 Nc5 15. Bc2 Be7 16. O-O-O O-O 17. Rhe1 Be6 18. Nd4 Rfc8 19. Bg3 Bf6 $15 {0-1 (61) Binas,J (2021) -Bobykin, K (2396) ICCF email 2013}  ) Nxc3 {Without going into the alternatives, the practice has shown this move to be Black's most reliable continuation.} 7. bxc3 {Capturing toward the centre is typically more principled} ( {than} 8. dxc3 {However, this move has received some love even from the top players in recent years. I have to say that I am a bit baffled by that because this approach seems very blend and harmless. Black can get a good position out of the opening in more than one way, although I prefer} a5 $1 { preparing to develop the dark-squared bishop to the most active diagonal.} ( {That said, even the more restrained} Be7 $5 {is fine and after} 9. e4 O-O 10. Be3 {Black does well with a thematic queen maneuver:} Qd6 $1 11. Bc4 Qg6 12. O-O Bh3 13. Ne1 {This was all seen in the game 1-0 (54) Topalov, V (2740) -Karjakin, S (2752) Abidjan 2019 and now Black should have taken the chance to improve his worst-placed piece} Na5 $146 14. Bd5 c6 15. Ba2 Be6 $11 { I should add that the presence of white pawn on a3 doesn't always do White a favour in this structure.}  ) 9. e4 Bc5 10. a4 ( 11. Bb5 {seems natural but achieves little after} O-O 12. O-O ( {since the greedy} 13. Bxc6 $2 bxc6 14. Nxe5 {fails miserably to} Re8 15. Nxc6 Qd5 $19  ) ( {I was surprised to find out that the continuation that I faced in a game against a much lower-rated opponent some 10 years ago was recently picked up by someone as strong as Vidit. Well, he tried something new