5 { }  ) {At this point, Black needs to choose a diagonal for the light-squared bishop and I would recommend} b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Re1 ( 14. Bb2 e4 ( {It's also fine to keep the tension for a moment with} Rfe8 $5  ) 15. Nd2 Na5 16. c4 c5 17. d5 Rae8 18. f4 exf3 19. Rxf3 Bc8 $1 $13 { 1/2-1/2 (27) Arutinian,D (2576) -Najer,E (2665) Rijeka 2010}  ) Rfe8 14. Bb2 Na5 {1-0 (22) Kramnik,V (2808) -Karjakin, S (2781) Stavanger 2017} {At this point, it was probably best for White to open the centre with} 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. c4 Qg5 $132 { though, of course, Black is doing quite well with thanks to his strong light-squared bishop and a slightly better pawn structure.}  ) ( 9. e4 {is a rare, although playable setup. Here is a good example of how Black should play} O-O 10. Be2 Qe7 ( {A slightly more aggressive plan} Kh8 $5 11. O-O f5 $132 { also looks playable.}  ) 11. O-O b6 12. d4 Bg4 13. Bg5 f6 14. Be3 Kh8 15. h3 Bd7 $13 { Black had a solid and harmonious setup in the game 0-1 (71) Bauer,C (2634) -Karpov,A (2670) Ajaccio 2007}  ) Qe7 { This is Black's main continuation here and it is difficult to find a good reason not to play this natural move.} ( {That said, I thought that I should mention a worthy alternative:} O-O $5 9. Bg2 Re8 10. d3 Bf5 11. Nd2 ( 12. e4 {1/2-1/2 (34) Bauer,C (2622) -Libiszewski,F (2520) Linares 2013} Be6 13. O-O Bc5 $13  ) Qd7 { This is the main difference compared to 8...Qe7 line.} 12. Rb1 Na5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (33) Morley,P (2391) -Cirrincione,G (2345) ICCF email 2013}  ) 9. d3 ( {White can hardly gain anything by allowing Black to push the e-pawn, as we can see in the following game:} 10. Bg2 e4 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. cxd4 Bf5 13. O-O O-O 14. f3 exf3 15. Qxf5 fxg2 16. Rf2 Rfe8 $11 {1/2 (53) Gelfand,B (2720) -Karjakin, S (2727) Moscow 2008}  ) {At this point, we have an important choice to make: shall we develop the light-squared bishop to h1-a8 diagonal or leave it on its current diagonal. I've thought about this issue for some time and concluded that I'd prefer the latter and therefore} O-O { is my main suggestion in this database.} ( {The reason why I am less in favour of} b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 {even though it is a perfectly playable continuation is that after} 11. O-O O-O 12. e4 Na5 13. Nh4 { the bishop is missed on the h3-c8 diagonal and Black needs to solve the issue of f5-square in less appealing ways, such as} g6 14. Bh6 Rfe8 {0-1 (41) Gurevich, M (2618) -Gupta, A (2565) Chalkida 2009} {and here, just to illustrate the issues created by the weakening ...g6-move, White has a strong attacking idea:} 15. f4 $1 $146 exf4 16. Nf3 $3 fxg3 17. Ng5 gxh2+ 18. Kh1 Rf8 19. d4 $40  ) 10. Bg2 Bd7 11. O-O Rae8 $13 {So, we have a very interesting middlegame ahead of us. It is not surprising that even some top players have played this variation with White because white setup is quite flexible and offers chances to outplay the opponent, even if there is no objective ''opening advantage'' to speak of. But, I suppose that the same could be said about black position. Let us examine some of the most critical continuations:} 12. e4 ( {The other plan is} 13. Nd2 Kh8 { Naturally, we are tucking the king away before launching the f-pawn.} 14. Bb2 {This is a slightly odd follow-up.} ( 15. Nc4 $5 {seems more to the point. For example:} f5 16. Nxd6 cxd6 17. f4 b6 $13  ) f5 15. c4 {Sometimes strong players trust each other too much.} f4 ( Nd4 $1 16. Bxd4 exd4 {would have been stronger since the pawn on b7 might as well be poisoned.} 17. Bxb7 c6 $40  ) 16. Ne4 { It's difficult to imagine that White could be worse with such a powerful knight.} Qf7 17. Rad1 Be7 18. Kh1 Bg4 19. Bf3 Bxf3+ 20. exf3 $11 {1/2-1/2 (78) Artemiev, V (2711) -Fedoseev,V (2674) Moscow 2020}  ) Na5 { This is one of several decent options for Black.} ( f5 13. exf5 Bxf5 { also looks okay, although I'd probably prefer one of the alternatives considering the long term outpost that White is getting on e4. For example:} 14. Nh4 Bc8 15. Be3 Kh8 16. Rfe1 Qf7 17. Nf3 $1 Qg6 18. Nd2 Bf5 19. Ne4 $14  ) ( Bc5 $5 13. Bb2 Qf6 $13  ) 13. Nh4 { We have seen how unpleasant this idea can be when black bishop is on b7. This is a different story because f5-square is well-protected.} ( 14. d4 f6 $11 { creates a typical stonewall in the center.}  ) ( 14. a4 c5 $132  ) b6 14. Nf5 Qf6 { With the pressure on f5, White needs to decide what to do with the knight.} 15. Ne3 ( 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 17. f4 f6 $132  ) Be6 16. Bb2 Bc5 $13 {  with a complex battle that ended in Black's favor in 0-1 (43) Gashimov,V (2760) -Wang Yue (2709) Ningbo 2011}  *

