{openings101.org. In this short chapter, we will examine sidelines that arise after a specific move order:} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e3 {White keeps the knight on g1 for the time being. In some cases, it can be developed to e2, but as we will see, there are other ways that White can try to justify this move order.} ( {If White begins with} 4. a3 {then after} d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {he is still most likely to transpose to the main line in this chapter by playing} 6. e3 ( {unless he goes for the Boleslavsky type of position with} 7. e4 Nb6 8. Nf3 Bg4 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O {0-1 (37) Adell Corts, F (2175) -Perez Cameselle, F Madrid 1997} Bxf3 $5 $146 11. Bxf3 Nd4 12. d3 c6 $11  ) ( {or} 7. Nf3 {which transposes to 4.a3 variation from Chapter 11 after} Nc6  ) Nc6 {-3.e3 Nc6 4.a3} ( {As I edited the text above, I realized that we could also play} Nxc3 $5 7. bxc3 Bd6 8. d4 O-O {transposing to the type of position that was examined in the previous chapter.}  )  ) Nc6 {This move is the most consistent with our general strategy. At this point, White can simply transpose to the main line that was discussed in chapters 6 and 7 by playing 4. Nf3.} ( d5 {is a tad premature since} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bd6 7. d4 { puts some unnecessary pressure to decide how to defend the e5-pawn.} Nc6 8. Bb5  ) ( {The main alternatives:} Bb4 4. Nge2 {(reversed Rossolimo)}  ) ( {and} c6 {(reversed Alapin) are definitely worthy of consideration, although they are not such principled choices considering our reversed 'open' Sicilian setup.}  ) {Or he can try to trick or surprise us with some of the less popular alternatives. Let us take a look at each of them in turn:} 4. a3 ( 5. g4 { is a modern approach that used to be quite trendy for a while, until it was found that Black can actually play} d5 $1 {The whole premise behind the thrust of the g-pawn is that Black cannot play this move. However, it turns out that after} 6. g5 d4 7. gxf6 dxc3 8. fxg7 Bxg7 $1 {we achieve excellent compensation for the sacrificed pawn no matter how White recaptures on c3.} ( cxd2+ {is playable, but much less impressive.} 9. Bxd2 Bxg7 10. Bc3 $13 {1/2-1/2 (28) Perina,G (2298) -Sciallero,V (2273) ICCF email 2018}  ) 9. dxc3 {This recapture is slightly better than the alternatives, objectively speaking,} ( {After} 10. bxc3 {the move} e4 $1 { makes white position look like a Swiss cheese.} 11. Ne2 $2 ( 12. Ba3 Ne5 13. Bc5 Qh4 $36  ) Ne5 12. Bg2 Nd3+ $19 {0-1 (47) Trent,L (2399) -Rensch,D (2402) Chess.com INT 2021}  ) ( {White could also decline the sacrifice with} 10. d3 { but his position remains worse anyway after} cxb2 11. Bxb2 Bf5 12. Qb3 Qd7 13. Rd1 O-O-O $17 {1-0 (71) Trent,L (2399) -Rensch,D (2402) Chess.com INT 2021}  ) Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 e4 $1 { Despite being down a pawn, black position seems much easier to play.} 11. Kc2 Ne5 12. Ne2 Bd7 $15  ) ( 5. Qb3 {is a very rare yet sensible move. White prevents Black from pushing the d-pawn two squares forward while also discouraging 4...Bb4. In the following game, one of the world's leading opening specialists, GM Anish Giri, provided a good blueprint how to meet this sideline:} g6 ( {If you are willing to explore new paths, then you might consider:} b6 $5 $146 6. d3 ( {Black's main idea is to meet} 7. Nf3 {with} e4 8. Ng5 Qe7 9. Qc2 Nb4 10. Qb1 {and at the end we can support the central pawn with} Bb7 $132  ) Bb7 7. Nf3 g6 8. Be2 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. a3 Qe7 11. Qc2 Nd8 $1 $11  ) 6. Nf3 Bg7 7. d4 exd4 8. exd4 O-O 9. Be2 d6 ( {Black could also utilize his slight lead in development with a Gruenfeld-like pawn sacrifice:} Re8 $5 $146 10. O-O d5 $1 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Qxd5 13. Nxd5 Rxe2 14. Nxc7 Rb8 $44  ) 10. O-O Re8 { We have a KID type of position on the board. Black has good counterplay in the centre, as we can see in the variations below:} 11. h3 ( 12. Re1 Bf5 $1 13. h3 ( 14. Qxb7 a5 15. Qxc6 Bd7 $11  ) Ne4 14. Be3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 b6 $11  ) ( 12. d5 Ne5 13. Nxe5 Rxe5 14. Bf4 Re8 15. Rae1 Ne4 $11  ) Ne4 12. Nxe4 Rxe4 13. Be3 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Bf3 Rh4 16. Bxd4 Rxd4 17. Bxb7 Bxb7 18. Qxb7 Rxc4 19. Rac1 $11 {1/2-1/2 (25) Carlsen,M (2872) -Giri,A (2768) Wijk aan Zee 2020}  ) ( 5. d4 {was once played by the great Viktor Korchnoi, although it is hardly a great move.} Bb4 6. d5 ( {Interestingly, in the event of} 7. Nf3 {we can take the game into the exchange French territory by playing} exd4 8. exd4 O-O 9. Be2 d5 10. O-O dxc4 11. Bxc4 Bg4 { Black has a great version of the IQP.} 12. Be3 Qd6 13. Rc1 Rae8 $15 {0-1 (52) Konstantinov,M (2361) -Pijl,R (2431) LSS email 2014}  ) Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Ne7 8. d6 cxd6 9. Qxd6 {White has opened the center but it took him three consecutive moves with one pawn and one queen move to do that. Black surely has ways to punish such original opening play.} Qa5 ( O-O $5 $146 {is even stronger since} 10. Qxe5 Re8 $36 { would give Black a strong initiative thanks to the lead in development.}  ) 10. Qb4 Qc7 11. Ba3 Nc6 {1/2 (25) Kortschnoj,V (2639) -Kasparov,G (2849) Zuerich 2001} 12. Qb2 d6 13. Rd1 Ne4 14. Bd3 Nc5 15. Bxc5 dxc5 16. Be4 O-O $11  ) ( 5. Qc2 {is an inaccurate way to play the Reversed Taimanov because of} d5 6. cxd5 Nb4 $1 { (this is why 4.a3 is more accurate)} 7. Qb1 ( 8. Qa4+ {is perhaps more critical, but also contains more risk for White.} Bd7 9. Bb5 ( 10. Qb3 $2 Bf5 11. d3 Bxd3 12. Bxd3 Nxd3+ 13. Ke2 Nc5 $17 {0-1 (79) Langenfeld,O (1923) -Borrink,J (2050) Rotenburg 2008}  ) c6 ( {If Black wants, he can also simplify matters with} Nbxd5 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Qxd7+ Kxd7 12. Nf3 Bd6 13. Ke2 $11  ) 10. dxc6 bxc6 11. Be2 Bf5 {and Black has excellent play for a mere pawn, for example:} 12. Kf1 Be7 13. Nf3 e4 $44  ) Nbxd5 8. d3 { White should play this move before developing the knight to f3} ( {as we can see in the line:} 9. Nf3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 e4 11. Ne5 Bd6 12. Qb5+ Nd7 $15 {0-1 (44) Dreisch,J (2106) -Horvath,M (2334) ICCF email 2016}  ) Bb4 9. Bd2 O-O 10. Nf3 Re8 11. e4 Nxc3 12. bxc3 {Black was already doing well in the game 1/2 (32) Vallejo Pons,F (2648) -Smirin,I (2676)