{openings101.org. The final chapter is devoted to various move orders without Nc3. As usual, White often tries to steer the game toward similar positions with colors reversed and an extra tempo, so I will explain these subleties where necessary.} 1. c4 ( 2. e4 c5 3. Nf3 e6 ( Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 {Nimzo-Rubinstein variation} 5. Nc3 e6 ( Nxc3 6. dxc3 Nc6 7. h4 e6 8. Bf4 Qc7 9. Qd2 h6 10. Bd3 b6 11. Be4 Bb7 12. c4 Na5 13. Bxb7 Nxb7 14. O-O-O $14 {1-0 (59) Carlsen,M (2856) -Duda,J (2760) Warsaw 2021}  ) 6. Ne4 $5 f5 7. Nc3 $14 Nc7 $6 8. d4 $16  ) ( d6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 a6 7. Be2 e5 8. Nb3 {Najdorf: Classical Be2 variation} Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Kh1  ) 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 ( a6 6. Bd3 {Kan Sicilian}  ) 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. Be3 {Taimanov Sicilian main variation} a6 8. Qd2 Nf6 9. O-O-O Be7 10. f3 b5 11. g4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bb7 13. Kb1 O-O 14. h4 b4 15. Na4 d5 $13 {1-0 (65) So,W (2772) -Artemiev,V (2704) chess24. com INT 2021}  ) e5 2. d3 {When playing this way, White typically go for the reversed Scheveningen without Nc3 or the reversed Najdorf.} ( {On the other hand,} 3. e3 Nf6 4. a3 {leads to reversed Kan variation after} d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {If you refer to 1.e4 - Kan Sicilian above, you will realize that this is virtually the same position after move four, but here it is White to move. Nevertheless, just as in the normal Kan, we can often develop the bishop to d6 (d3 for White) since there is no pressure on the knight.} 6. Nf3 ( {In the event of} 7. Qc2 Bd6 8. b4 O-O 9. Bb2 {we can take advantage of the fact that the knight is still on b8 to play} a5 $1 10. b5 Nd7 { White queenside pawns will become vulnerable soon, as the following variation illustrates.} 11. Nf3 Re8 12. d3 N7b6 13. Nbd2 Qe7 14. Be2 Bd7 $15  ) Bd6 7. Qc2 O-O 8. Bc4 {This is a typical way to develop your pieces in the Kan Sicilian. In most cases, the knight retreats to b3 (here b6) , but in this particular position, I am more in the favor of} Nf6 $5 $146 { since the knight controls the kingside and centre better from this square. Black is not going to be playing ...f7-f5 with the white bishop on a2-g8 diagonal any time soon, so we cannot say that Nf6 is really in the way of the f-pawn.} ( Nb6 9. Ba2 c5 {is more standard. After} 10. Nc3 Nc6 {White can play a thematic Paulsen move} 11. h4 $1 $13 { though, when it becomes clear that the knight is missing on the kingside.}  ) 9. Nc3 a6 { Not the most common way to complete your development in such positions, but it looks pretty good.} 10. O-O b5 11. Ba2 ( 12. Be2 {is more passive. Black gets a good version of the reversed Hedgehog after} Bb7 13. d3 c5 14. b3 Nc6 15. Bb2 Re8 $13  ) Bb7 12. Ng5 { It's only natural for White to play like this in order to fight for the complex of light squares. Black keeps the balance, nevertheless, by responding with} Nbd7 13. d3 c5 14. a4 Bc6 $11  ) ( 3. Nf3 {is another attempt to get the reversed Nimzo-Rubinstein variation or Alekhine Defence reversed with an extra tempo if you will. It is a pet variation of the Russian 2600+ GM Alexander Rakhmanov.} e4 4. Nd4 Nc6 {You can compare this position to the regular Nimzo-Rubinstein above. White's extra tempo matters only if he plays} 5. e3 ( 6. Nxc6 dxc6 { is very similar to the Carlsen-Duda game with colours reversed. I am not sure why White would voluntarily play like this because this structure is known to be at least slightly more pleasant for Black and his extra tempo is virtually meaningless.} 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. e3 Bf5 9. Qb3 b6 10. Qc2 Qd7 11. h3 h5 $1 12. b3 a5 13. Bb2 h4 $15 {0-1 (31) Rakhmanov,A (2634) -Savchenko,B (2562) Sochi 2018}  ) ( 6. Nc2 {should be met by} d5 {without delay.} 7. cxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qe5 {To avoid getting squeezed in the centre, White should play} 9. d4 exd3 10. Qxd3 Nf6 $11 {Black is already very comfortable.} 11. e4 Nb4 $5 12. Nxb4 Bxb4 13. Qb5+ Qxb5 14. Bxb5+ Bd7 15. Bd3 O-O-O 16. f3 Be6 17. Be2 Nd7 $132 {1/2-1/2 (51) Rakhmanov, A (2610) -Shyam, S (2481) Dubai 2014}  ) Nf6 {I believe that it is best to continue developing.} ( {In a similar position with colours reversed, the critical line goes} Ne5 6. f4 Nc6 {and White usually manage to prove an advantage in the opening. However, when colours are reversed, things are different because} 7. Nc2 {cannot be met by} d5 8. cxd5 { with the same effect as in the abovementioned line since the knight is not on f6. Black is forced to recapture with the queen} Qxd5 {when} 9. Nc3 $13 { is rather unclear.}  ) ( Nxd4 {is another reasonable approach. I share an interesting old game below mostly to show how Richard Reti was a visionary - his hypermodernist ideas are being experimented with on a grandmaster level even to this day.} 6. exd4 Qf6 7. d5 ( {White could focus on his development instead with} 8. Nc3 $5 Qxd4 9. Be2 Nf6 10. O-O d5 11. d3 $44  ) Bc5 8. Qe2 Qe7 9. Nc3 f5 10. d3 Nf6 11. Bg5 O-O 12. O-O-O {1/2-1/2 (47) Reti,R-Saemisch,F Brno 1928} d6 $132  ) 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Qc2 ( {Interestingly, if White plays} 8. Qb3 {then we transpose into a line that was discussed in Chapter 6 (5.Qb3 e4 6.Nd4) .}  ) Nxd4 8. exd4 {At this point, I believe that we have a slight improvement over the game ½-½ (30) Rakhmanov,A (2606) -Sasikiran,K (2675) Linares 2019 in} c6 $5 9. a3 ( 10. Nxe4 {cannot be taken anyway because of} Qe7  ) Ba5 {and Black is doing well in any case:} 10. d5 $5 ( 11. d3 d5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Bd2 exd3 14. Bxd3 Nf6 15. O-O O-O $11 { 0-1 (55) Dreisch,J (2106) -Brodt,A (2352) ICCF email 2016}  ) cxd5 11. cxd5 Qe7 12. Bc4 O-O 13. O-O d6 14. d3 Bf5 $11  ) ( {Finally, we have} 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Nc6 5. e3 {which could also arise via a popular variation of the Larsen opening: 1.b3 e5 2.Bb2 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 4.c4!?} ( {Its alternative} 6. Nf3 {received some attention from strong players lately primarily because of} e4 7. Nd4 Bc5 8. Nf5 $1 {This move gives White some interesting practical opportunities, even if it is not completely sound by objective standards. Healthy development virtually always trumps such early aggressive attempts. Let us see how:} O-O ( d5 {is also playable...} 9. Nxg7+ Kf8 10. cxd5 Bd4 $1 11. Nc3 $1 Nb4 12. Nh5 $1 Nxh5 13. e3 $13 {...but too complicated to understand, let alone play in an actual game.}  ) 9. e3 d5 $1 10. cxd5 Nb4 ( {A famous blunder} Nxd5 $4 {made all White's dreams come true} 11. Qg4 {1-0 (9) Adhiban,B (2660) -Navara,D (2697) chess24.com INT 2021}  ) 11. Ng3 ( {The intermezzo} 12. Qc1 { makes virtually no difference compared to the main line if we play} Bb6  ) Nfxd5 $1 {  This is the key move. We are willing to sacrifice the central pawn; in fact, we are inviting White to take it. Our lead in development justifies this decision.} 12. Qc1 ( {Probably the sanest thing that White can do is to play} 13. a3 Nd3+ 14. Bxd3 exd3 15. Nc3 Re8 16. Rc1 Bf8 $11 {and complete his development.}  ) ( 13. Nxe4 $2 {is refuted by brute force:} Bf5 14. d3 Bxe4 15. dxe4 Nxe3 $1 $19  ) Bb6 $1 {Nothing changes, we keep sacrificing the central pawn.} 13. a3 ( 14. Nxe4 {is far too risky, as the following correspondence game showed:} Re8 15. Nbc3 Nf4 $3 16. exf4 Qh4 $40 17. Be2 Bxf2+ 18. Kf1 Bd4 19. d3 Bf5 20. a3 Nc6 21. Qe1 Qxf4+ 22. Bf3 Rad8 $40 { with a wonderful attacking position for Black in 0-1 (35) Novak,J (2534) -Rubinas,P (2557) ICCF email 2008}  ) Nd3+ 14. Bxd3 exd3 15. O-O Be6 $15 { White queen is not placed well on c1, which is why 10. a3 was a relatively better choice for White in a similar position.} 16. Nc3 c5 17. Kh1 Rc8 18. f4 f6 $17 { 0-1 (38) Adhiban,B (2660) -Navara,D (2697) chess24.com INT 2021}  ) d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. a3 { This preventive move is necessary. Now we have some sort of a reversed Kan/ Scheveningen Sicilian on the board.} ( 8. Bb5 $6 Ndb4  ) {Black has two reasonable directions. As in many previously discussed reversed Sicilians, we could go for a more aggressive English-attack type of development with} Be6 $5 ( {or peaceful development with} Bd6 {White usually continue} 8. d3 { planning to get a version of the Scheveningen with the knight on d2 and (often) c4.} ( 9. Bc4 {makes less sense here due to} Nb6  ) O-O 9. Nf3 Qe7 { Black's plan is, as usual, to push ...f7-f5 and mobilize his forces to execute one of the central breaks at the right moment.} 10. Be2 ( 11. Nbd2 { is an interesting alternative plan, suggested by GM Adhiban in his Chessable 1.b3 course. The idea is to develop the bishop to g2, transposing into a reversed Dragon of sorts.} f5 12. Nc4 {Here, it is important to remember to respond energetically with} b5 $1 13. Nxd6 cxd6 { This recapture strengthens the black centre and opens the c-file.} 14. g3 {and now we have two good options:} Nd8 {  is a positional option, preparing to regroup our pieces in a useful way.} ( f4 $5 $146 15. gxf4 Bg4 $1 {is much more ambitious and, consequently, double-edged. Here is a possible line:} 16. Rg1 h5 17. h3 exf4 18. e4 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 Ne5 20. Qxh5 Nf6 $44 21. Qe2 Rac8 22. d4 Nf7 $132 {The position is very complicated, but I like Black's chances because of a safer king and better development.}  ) 15. Bg2 Bb7 16. O-O Nf6 17. b4 a6 18. a4 Nf7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (26) Punzon Moraleda,J (2481) -Havumaki,A (2416) ICCF email 2016}  ) f5 11. Qc2 Kh8 12. Nbd2 ( 13. b4 $6 e4 14. dxe4 fxe4 15. Nfd2 Bf5 $15  ) a5 13. O-O Bd7 14. Nc4 Rae8 15. Rac1 {All of the moves so far have been natural and self-explanatory. In the ensuing middlegame, Black needs to make sure to deal with c4-knight first before attempting anything in the centre.} b5 $1 ( e4 $2 { is premature because of} 16. Nfd2 Nf6 17. Nxd6 cxd6 18. dxe4 fxe4 19. Nc4 d5 20. Nb6 $16  ) 16. Nxd6 cxd6 17. Rfe1 Rc8 18. Qd2 Be6 $13 { with a complex struggle in ½-½ (56) Salgado Lopez,I (2584) -Vitiugov,N (2722) Playchess.com INT 2020}  ) 8. Qc2 {Most players continue like this by analogy to the Taimanov variation.} ( {In one correspondence game, White decided to omit the queen move and continued} 9. b4 f6 10. Nf3 Qd7 11. Be2 g5 12. b5 Nce7 13. O-O g4 14. Ne1 O-O-O 15. Nd3 { That's a fairly typical knight-resetting manoeuvre in the Paulsen. Nevertheless, Black was doing well after} Ng6 $13 {0-1 (18) Punzon Moraleda,J (2502) -Rio,R (2447) ICCF email 2020}  ) Qd7 9. Nf3 f6 10. b4 O-O-O $132 { After several natural moves by both sides, we have virtually reached an important theoretical position from the main line of Taimanov Sicilian, with colours reversed, of course. Please compare it to the game So-Artemiev at the beginning of the chapter. There are some differences, such as Bb2 being developed instead of Nc3 and Be2. However, the most important thing to notice is that White doesn't have an extra tempo here and this is because he spent two tempi with his b-pawn! I believe that this circumstance gives us the full right to play this position ambitiously as Black. Let us consider White's main options.} 11. b5 { This way, White sidelines black knight and prepares to carry out the central d2-d4 break.} ( 12. Nc3 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 g5 14. h3 ( {It was better to be more expedient with the central break:} 15. b5 Ne7 16. d4 g4 17. Nd2 $13  ) Kb8 15. Be2 $6 {White's play in this game is too slow.} ( {This was the last opportunity to play} 16. d4 {under favorable circumstances.} Bf5 17. Qb2 $13  ) Rg8 16. b5 Ne7 17. d4 e4 $1 18. Nd2 f5 19. Nc4 Nd5 20. Ne5 Qe8 21. Bd2 Bd6 $17 { Grischuk's play, on the other hand, has been textbook.} 22. O-O Bxe5 23. dxe5 h5 24. a4 g4 $40 {0-1 (36) Ivanisevic,I (2606) -Grischuk,A (2776) Chess.com INT 2021}  ) Na5 12. d4 e4 $1 { This strong and thematic move allows Black to close the center favorably.} ( {It would be much worse to open the center with} exd4 $6 13. Nxd4 $16  ) 13. Nfd2 ( 14. Qxe4 $4 {is bad because after} Bf5 15. Qh4 g5 { the queen would soon find itself trapped.}  ) f5 14. Nc3 {Now we have a position that looks a lot like some branch of the Steinitz French. Black's play in the recent game 0-1 (46) Solon, N (2306) -Sadhwani, R (2609) Chess.com INT 2021 could be improved with} Nb6 $5 $146 { } 15. Be2 ( 16. Na4 { neglects development and allows us to take the initiative with} f4 $5 17. exf4 Bf5 $36  ) Qf7 $13 { This way, we ensure that the knight on a5 will always have a safe square to go to if attacked. Black is doing well already, but let us examine a sample line to get some more insight about the position:} 16. Na4 Kb8 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. dxc5 Nbc4 19. Nxc4 Bxc4 20. Bxc4 Nxc4 21. Bd4 f4 $1 $132  ) Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. a3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {As noted above, White has two independent options here:} 6. e3 {This clearly indicates White's intention to play the reversed Scheveningen.} ( {and} 7. e4 {which is basically the reversed Najdorf with an extra tempo for White. The key difference compared to Boleslavsky structure positions with the knight on c3 (that were examined in Chapter 10) is that White is more flexible with queen's knight. It can be employed to d2, which neutralizes the effect of ...Bg4 pin. I would, therefore, suggest that we change our response and play} Nb6 ( {instead of} Nf6 {which was my main recommendation in a similar position in Chapter 10.} 8. Be2 {The key difference is that} Bg4 {is not nearly as strong as there because of} 9. Nbd2 { and Black cannot take full control over d4-square anymore.}  ) 8. Be2 ( {The main idea behind putting the knight to b6 was to be able to push the f-pawn. In the event of} 9. Be3 {we could even do it at once} f5 $5 10. Be2 ( {Black doesn't mind} 11. exf5 {since it helps him develop his queenside pieces quickly} Bxf5 12. Nc3 {0-1 (34) Makarian,R (2442) -Clarke,B (2429) Lichess.org INT 2020 and here} Qd7 $5 $146 { looks like the right move, pretty much forcing White to play} 13. d4 exd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Qxd4 16. Bxd4 O-O-O $11  ) f4 11. Bc1 { If you are familiar with the Najdorf, you will know that such backward bishop moves are not uncommon in this type of position. Black has released the tension in the centre, so White is hoping to exploit this with Nbd2, b4, Bb2, etc.} Bg4 12. Nbd2 a5 $1 { Not only stopping 11.b4, but also securing c5-square for the bishop.} 13. b3 Bc5 14. Bb2 Qd6 15. O-O O-O 16. Qc2 { Black had solid control over dark squares in the centre in the game 1-0 (73) Bocharov, D (2528) -Dominguez Perez, L (2758) Chess.com INT 2020 and it would have been the best to fortify the bishop on c5 with} Nd7 $146 { } 17. Rfc1 ( 18. Nc4 Qe7 $15  ) b6 $13  ) Be7 9. O-O O-O {This position arises in the Najdorf variation with colours reversed and with Black to move. You can compare it to the Najdorf: Classical Be2 variation at the beginning of the chapter. The interesting thing about that position is that before pushing f2-f4, White often plays a waiting move like Kh1, basically waiting for his opponent to play ...Be6. If we translate it to this position, it seems like White's extra tempo isn't a big deal because ...Kh8 is a move that we can also do without. So, after} 10. Be3 {we can safely play} f5 {The reason we typically wait for White to play Be3 before pushing ...f5 is that he cannot play b3/b4, Bb2 to attack the e5-pawn anymore. Another benefit is that we can win a tempo with ...f4 if White decides to ignore the f-pawn.} ( {For those who prefer a manoeuvring battle,} Re8 $5 11. Nbd2 a5 12. Rc1 Bf8 $13 {is a perfectly playable alternative.}  ) {White has a pretty wide choice of options here, so let us take a look at each of them in turn:} 11. b4 { prepares Be3-c5, should Black attack the bishop.} ( 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Nc3 {is rather harmless. Black is doing well after} Qe8 $5 14. d4 exd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Rd8 $11  ) ( 12. Re1 f4 13. Bd2 { is a fairly typical idea in the Najdorf, but it's perhaps only good enough to equalize for White.} Bg4 14. Bc3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 a5 16. Qc2 Kh8 17. Nd2 Bc5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (36) Kruse,H (2506) -Larwinski,P (2506) FICGS email 2021}  ) ( 12. Bd2 $5 {looks like a clever improvement over the previous variation, but the thing is that after} Kh8 13. Bc3 Bd6 14. Nbd2 Qe7 $13 { there is still tension in the centre since we haven't pushed the pawn to f4, so we can open some files with ...fxe4 next.}  ) a6 12. Nbd2 f4 13. Bc5 Bxc5 14. bxc5 Nd7 15. Rc1 {0-1 (55) Kokarev,D (2621) -Loskutova,V (2110) Khanty-Mansiysk 2020 In this position, Black could have acted more decisively:} Qf6 $146 16. Nb3 g5 $132  ) a5 { We are in no rush to develop considering that White has mostly played with his pawns so far. So, it makes sense to take the time to stop b2-b4.} 7. Be2 {At this point, we can choose from two reasonable setups. Unlike in a similar position with the knight on c3 (from Chapter 11) , here we can also develop the bishop to} Bd6 ( {Alternatively, we can simply follow the default development scheme:} Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qc2 Be6 10. b3 f5 11. Bb2 Bf6 12. Nbd2 {This is the key difference compared to positions from Chapter 11. The knight is often headed toward c4-square to put pressure on the central pawn. We should, therefore, play} Qe7 13. Rac1 ( 14. Nc4 {can be conveniently parried with} Bf7  ) ( 14. Rfe1 $5 g5 15. d4 e4 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Bg7 $13  ) Kh8 14. Rfe1 { This is a standard move in the Scheveningen, as already discussed in Chapter 11. Both White and Black are trying to execute their e4-break under the right circumstances.} Rad8 ( Bg8 $5 { has a similar idea as the main line.} 15. e4 ( 16. Bf1 e4 $1  ) Nf4 16. Bf1 fxe4 17. Nxe4 Bd5 $13  ) 15. Bf1 {0-1 (45) Grischuk,A (2782) -Caruana,F (2799) Saint Louis 2017} ( 16. Qc5 Qe8 $1  ) {Here, Black could have been quicker with} e4 $1 $132 {relying on a nice pinning tactic to protect the pawn indirectly.} 16. dxe4 fxe4 17. Nxe4 $2 Bf5 $19  ) 8. b3 O-O 9. Bb2 f5 10. Nbd2 Qe7 11. Qc2 {This position is quite similar to the 7...Be7 line, but the difference is that the light-squared bishop should be developed to} Bd7 { here, so as not to interfere with black pieces on the e-file. We don't need to be worried about White pinning d5-knight.} 12. g3 Kh8 13. O-O Rae8 14. Rfe1 e4 $1 $36 {1-0 (52) Shankland,S (2725) -Van Foreest,J (2612) Wijk aan Zee 2019. Black should be happy about the opening outcome because he mobilized all his pieces and took the initiative with